WEBVTT

00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:14.940
Hi everyone, I'm Fabio from Freewings and today we're going to tackle the meteo topic together.

00:00:14.940 --> 00:00:21.940
It's mainly about exam preparation, or meteo basics in general.

00:00:22.160 --> 00:00:27.160
There are basically two ways you can learn meteorology.

00:00:27.160 --> 00:00:31.160
One is the minimum effort, just for the theory exam.

00:00:31.160 --> 00:00:34.160
And of course there's a lot more weather knowledge

00:00:34.160 --> 00:00:37.160
you can learn beyond that.

00:00:37.160 --> 00:00:40.160
There are basically no limits.

00:00:40.160 --> 00:00:43.160
There are five-volume tomes about meteorology.

00:00:43.160 --> 00:00:47.160
This course is really geared toward the basics.

00:00:47.160 --> 00:00:51.160
The course is also definitely useful for already-licensed pilots,

00:00:51.160 --> 00:00:54.160
maybe to refresh weather knowledge,

00:00:54.160 --> 00:00:56.160
or to learn some new things.

00:00:56.160 --> 00:01:00.160
There's definitely interesting material in here for experienced pilots too.

00:01:01.160 --> 00:01:05.160
But of course the course is mainly geared toward paraglider pilots,

00:01:05.160 --> 00:01:09.160
so that you can hopefully apply this weather knowledge well.

00:01:09.160 --> 00:01:12.160
Where the theory might be a bit dry

00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:14.160
and a lot of things are hard to understand,

00:01:14.160 --> 00:01:18.160
we'll dive right in.

00:01:18.160 --> 00:01:21.160
Into this exciting field of weather knowledge.

00:01:21.160 --> 00:01:24.160
One thing that's always close to my heart,

00:01:24.160 --> 00:01:26.160
especially when it comes to meteorology,

00:01:26.160 --> 00:01:29.160
is that there are two areas.

00:01:29.160 --> 00:01:32.160
One is theoretical weather knowledge,

00:01:32.160 --> 00:01:35.160
where you understand a lot of theory.

00:01:35.160 --> 00:01:38.160
But the actual weather plays out in practice,

00:01:38.160 --> 00:01:40.160
and that takes a lot of experience.

00:01:40.160 --> 00:01:44.160
In flying practice, in meteo practice.

00:01:44.160 --> 00:01:46.160
Lots of it ties into the actual flying.

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:49.160
The weather gets observed and analysed again and again,

00:01:49.160 --> 00:01:52.160
and the theory is constantly cross-checked against practice.

00:01:52.160 --> 00:01:54.160
That's also really important.

00:01:54.160 --> 00:01:57.160
But in this section it's actually about theory

00:01:57.160 --> 00:02:01.160
and about a basic understanding of weather.

00:02:01.160 --> 00:02:03.860
First of all, the biggest question:

00:02:03.860 --> 00:02:05.860
where does weather actually take place?

00:02:05.860 --> 00:02:08.860
That's our atmosphere.

00:02:08.860 --> 00:02:12.860
The atmosphere around the Earth is divided

00:02:12.860 --> 00:02:13.860
into different layers.

00:02:13.860 --> 00:02:16.860
The stratosphere, mesosphere, troposphere.

00:02:16.860 --> 00:02:20.860
For us, the most relevant

00:02:20.860 --> 00:02:22.860
is the troposphere,

00:02:22.860 --> 00:02:25.860
where it meets the boundary

00:02:25.860 --> 00:02:26.860
called the tropopause,

00:02:26.860 --> 00:02:28.860
and in this layer

00:02:28.860 --> 00:02:31.860
is where most of the humidity sits,

00:02:31.860 --> 00:02:33.860
or most of the water vapour.

00:02:33.860 --> 00:02:36.020
And that's where weather happens,

00:02:36.020 --> 00:02:39.410
in the troposphere.

00:02:39.410 --> 00:02:41.410
It's extremely thin,

00:02:41.410 --> 00:02:43.410
if you look at it compared to the Earth,

00:02:43.410 --> 00:02:45.410
almost like the layer of an onion.

00:02:45.410 --> 00:02:47.410
(unclear)

00:02:47.410 --> 00:02:48.410
(unclear)

00:02:48.410 --> 00:02:49.410
(unclear)

00:02:49.410 --> 00:02:50.410
(unclear)

00:02:50.410 --> 00:02:51.410
(unclear)

00:02:51.410 --> 00:02:52.410
(unclear)

00:02:52.410 --> 00:02:54.410
Like the skin of an onion,

00:02:54.410 --> 00:02:56.410
it's really a very, very thin region

00:02:56.410 --> 00:02:58.410
where the weather happens

00:02:58.410 --> 00:03:00.410
and where we of course also move around.

00:03:00.410 --> 00:03:02.410
And as paraglider pilots,

00:03:02.410 --> 00:03:03.410
we actually only move

00:03:03.410 --> 00:03:04.410
in the very lowest layer

00:03:04.410 --> 00:03:06.410
of this troposphere.

00:03:06.410 --> 00:03:09.660
And what's important in theory,

00:03:09.660 --> 00:03:10.660
for the theory exam,

00:03:10.660 --> 00:03:11.660
is knowing

00:03:11.660 --> 00:03:13.660
the composition

00:03:13.660 --> 00:03:16.660
of the gases in this troposphere.

00:03:16.660 --> 00:03:17.660
That is,

00:03:17.660 --> 00:03:19.660
21% oxygen,

00:03:19.660 --> 00:03:21.660
which is important for us

00:03:21.660 --> 00:03:23.660
for breathing of course,

00:03:23.660 --> 00:03:25.660
about 78% nitrogen,

00:03:25.660 --> 00:03:27.660
and then there's about 1% noble gases,

00:03:27.660 --> 00:03:30.660
for example argon,

00:03:30.660 --> 00:03:31.660
but for us

00:03:31.660 --> 00:03:32.660
for meteorology

00:03:32.660 --> 00:03:34.660
that's not of great relevance,

00:03:34.660 --> 00:03:36.660
the remaining noble gases

00:03:36.660 --> 00:03:39.230
that are in there.

00:03:39.230 --> 00:03:40.230
Now,

00:03:40.230 --> 00:03:41.230
the troposphere

00:03:41.230 --> 00:03:43.230
is not

00:03:43.230 --> 00:03:46.230
the same thickness all around the globe,

00:03:46.230 --> 00:03:47.230
it's a bit thinner

00:03:47.230 --> 00:03:49.230
at the poles

00:03:49.230 --> 00:03:50.230
than at the equator,

00:03:50.230 --> 00:03:53.230
which has to do with the Earth's rotation.

00:03:53.230 --> 00:03:56.230
At the equator it's roughly 18 kilometres,

00:03:56.230 --> 00:03:58.230
and at the poles

00:03:58.230 --> 00:04:01.230
it's about 8 kilometres.

00:04:01.230 --> 00:04:03.230
For us in Europe,

00:04:03.230 --> 00:04:04.230
by latitude,

00:04:04.230 --> 00:04:06.230
where we mostly fly,

00:04:06.230 --> 00:04:07.230
let's say

00:04:07.230 --> 00:04:09.230
roughly 11 to 13 kilometres

00:04:09.230 --> 00:04:11.230
thickness of this troposphere,

00:04:11.230 --> 00:04:17.860
let's say 13,000 metres.

00:04:17.860 --> 00:04:19.150
Now,

00:04:19.150 --> 00:04:21.150
let's talk about the standard atmosphere.

00:04:21.150 --> 00:04:23.150
This is always important,

00:04:23.150 --> 00:04:24.150
in flight weather

00:04:24.150 --> 00:04:26.150
and especially the theory exam

00:04:26.150 --> 00:04:28.150
keeps asking

00:04:28.150 --> 00:04:30.150
about the standard atmosphere.

00:04:30.150 --> 00:04:33.150
That's the atmosphere

00:04:33.150 --> 00:04:35.150
where weather

00:04:35.150 --> 00:04:36.150
has completely balanced out,

00:04:36.150 --> 00:04:38.150
we have no high-pressure areas,

00:04:38.150 --> 00:04:39.150
no low-pressure areas,

00:04:39.150 --> 00:04:40.150
and different factors

00:04:40.150 --> 00:04:42.150
that influence us from outside.

00:04:42.150 --> 00:04:43.150
We'll look at those.

00:04:43.150 --> 00:04:45.150
When everything has balanced out,

00:04:45.150 --> 00:04:49.150
we arrive at what's called the standard atmosphere.

00:04:49.150 --> 00:04:51.150
It's basically a zero point,

00:04:51.150 --> 00:04:53.150
where everything has equalised.

00:04:53.150 --> 00:04:55.150
And there are a few numbers

00:04:55.150 --> 00:04:56.150
and facts,

00:04:56.150 --> 00:05:00.150
that the theory exam asks for.

00:05:00.150 --> 00:05:05.700
The important one is the temperature gradient with altitude,

00:05:05.700 --> 00:05:09.700
how the troposphere cools off.

00:05:09.700 --> 00:05:12.700
We say 6.5 degrees

00:05:12.700 --> 00:05:14.700
per 1000 metres of altitude,

00:05:14.700 --> 00:05:15.700
or per 100 metres,

00:05:15.700 --> 00:05:16.700
you can also say it as

00:05:16.700 --> 00:05:22.700
0.65 degrees per 100 metres.

00:05:22.700 --> 00:05:24.760
Then at the surface,

00:05:24.760 --> 00:05:25.760
in the standard atmosphere,

00:05:25.760 --> 00:05:27.760
we talk about 15 degrees,

00:05:27.760 --> 00:05:29.760
and at the tropopause

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:31.760
about minus 56 degrees.

00:05:31.760 --> 00:05:34.760
Especially those two numbers are important,

00:05:34.760 --> 00:05:38.760
to learn for the theory exam.

00:05:38.760 --> 00:05:48.340
The temperature gradient,

00:05:48.340 --> 00:05:50.340
depending on the weather situation,

00:05:50.340 --> 00:05:51.340
and the conditions,

00:05:51.340 --> 00:05:52.340
as you'll learn later,

00:05:52.340 --> 00:05:54.620
can of course vary.

00:05:54.620 --> 00:05:57.620
But for the standard atmosphere we say 6.5 degrees

00:05:57.620 --> 00:05:59.620
per 100 metres.

00:05:59.620 --> 00:06:01.620
That's the temperature.

00:06:01.620 --> 00:06:03.620
In the standard atmosphere we also talk about,

00:06:03.620 --> 00:06:04.620
the standard pressure,

00:06:04.620 --> 00:06:05.620
and the numbers

00:06:05.620 --> 00:06:07.620
you'll hear again and again,

00:06:07.620 --> 00:06:10.620
are 1013.25 hectopascals.

00:06:10.620 --> 00:06:11.620
The air pressure,

00:06:11.620 --> 00:06:14.620
when the whole troposphere

00:06:14.620 --> 00:06:15.620
is in balance,

00:06:15.620 --> 00:06:18.620
calculated at sea level,

00:06:18.620 --> 00:06:20.620
the air pressure is always the same,

00:06:20.620 --> 00:06:23.620
namely 1013.25 hectopascals.

00:06:23.620 --> 00:06:25.620
And the troposphere height,

00:06:25.620 --> 00:06:26.620
the highest,

00:06:26.620 --> 00:06:28.620
where the tropopause begins,

00:06:28.620 --> 00:06:31.620
is at 11 kilometres in the standard atmosphere.

00:06:33.420 --> 00:06:35.420
Another important thing about air pressure,

00:06:35.420 --> 00:06:37.420
how it decreases with altitude,

00:06:37.420 --> 00:06:38.420
is not linear,

00:06:38.420 --> 00:06:40.420
there's a rule of thumb.

00:06:40.420 --> 00:06:41.420
We can say that

00:06:41.420 --> 00:06:45.420
every 5500 metres of altitude

00:06:45.420 --> 00:06:47.420
the air pressure halves.

00:06:47.420 --> 00:06:49.420
So we can say,

00:06:49.420 --> 00:06:50.420
at 5500 metres,

00:06:50.420 --> 00:06:51.420
you'd have about 500,

00:06:51.420 --> 00:06:54.420
or 506 hectopascals.

00:06:54.420 --> 00:06:55.710
That's also a value,

00:06:55.710 --> 00:06:57.710
the 5500 metres,

00:06:57.710 --> 00:06:59.710
that's very important,

00:06:59.710 --> 00:07:00.710
for the theory exam,

00:07:00.710 --> 00:07:01.710
to learn.

00:07:01.710 --> 00:07:04.710
So pressure of course decreases with altitude.

00:07:04.710 --> 00:07:06.710
You can picture air pressure

00:07:06.710 --> 00:07:08.710
as a column of air

00:07:08.710 --> 00:07:09.710
above you,

00:07:09.710 --> 00:07:11.710
all the way up to the tropopause.

00:07:11.710 --> 00:07:13.710
And it's the same as water, for example,

00:07:13.710 --> 00:07:15.710
those who dive will know:

00:07:15.710 --> 00:07:17.710
the deeper you go in the water,

00:07:17.710 --> 00:07:19.710
the higher the pressure,

00:07:19.710 --> 00:07:21.710
the gravity of the Earth.

00:07:21.710 --> 00:07:22.710
And so we can say,

00:07:22.710 --> 00:07:24.710
the air pressure is of course

00:07:24.710 --> 00:07:26.710
highest at the lowest point,

00:07:26.710 --> 00:07:27.710
at sea level,

00:07:27.710 --> 00:07:29.710
and decreases with altitude.

00:07:29.710 --> 00:07:31.710
That has to do with gravity

00:07:31.710 --> 00:07:33.740
and with this column of air

00:07:33.740 --> 00:07:35.740
that presses down on us

00:07:35.740 --> 00:07:36.740
and so to speak

00:07:36.740 --> 00:07:38.740
generates air pressure.

00:07:38.740 --> 00:07:40.740
Quick summary of the numbers:

00:07:40.740 --> 00:07:43.740
1013.25, 15 degrees,

00:07:43.740 --> 00:07:46.740
and 0.65 per 100 metres,

00:07:46.740 --> 00:07:48.740
those are the numbers

00:07:48.740 --> 00:07:50.740
that are relevant for us

00:07:50.740 --> 00:07:53.740
for the standard atmosphere.

00:07:54.380 --> 00:07:55.380
Right.

00:07:55.380 --> 00:07:56.420
And if you think about it,

00:07:56.420 --> 00:07:58.420
the standard atmosphere

00:07:58.420 --> 00:08:00.420
is of course not always the same,

00:08:00.420 --> 00:08:02.420
as we experience daily

00:08:02.420 --> 00:08:04.420
with the weather.

00:08:04.420 --> 00:08:06.420
There's a motor that drives this,

00:08:06.420 --> 00:08:08.420
the sun that shines on the Earth,

00:08:08.420 --> 00:08:09.420
and acts on it,

00:08:09.420 --> 00:08:11.420
different land masses,

00:08:11.420 --> 00:08:13.420
and more water,

00:08:13.420 --> 00:08:15.420
different heating,

00:08:15.420 --> 00:08:17.420
different seasons too,

00:08:17.420 --> 00:08:19.420
with different sun angles depending on the season.

00:08:19.420 --> 00:08:22.420
The sun isn't always at the same height.

00:08:22.420 --> 00:08:25.420
Accordingly, all of this

00:08:25.420 --> 00:08:27.420
throws the standard atmosphere

00:08:27.420 --> 00:08:29.420
out of equilibrium,

00:08:29.420 --> 00:08:31.420
and there are fluctuations,

00:08:31.420 --> 00:08:32.420
in air pressure,

00:08:32.420 --> 00:08:34.420
and that gives us our whole weather system.

00:08:34.420 --> 00:08:36.420
And it's a really important motor

00:08:36.420 --> 00:08:37.420
that

00:08:37.420 --> 00:08:38.420
throws things out of balance,

00:08:38.420 --> 00:08:40.420
and influences

00:08:40.420 --> 00:08:41.420
different weather.

00:08:41.420 --> 00:08:43.420
And we'll look at this together,

00:08:43.420 --> 00:08:46.610
what kind of influence that has.

00:08:46.610 --> 00:08:48.500
The sun,

00:08:48.500 --> 00:08:50.730
that shines on the Earth,

00:08:50.730 --> 00:08:52.820
warms

00:08:52.820 --> 00:08:53.820
the ground,

00:08:53.820 --> 00:08:54.820
that's important.

00:08:54.820 --> 00:08:55.820
So the sun

00:08:55.820 --> 00:08:56.820
doesn't actually warm air masses

00:08:56.820 --> 00:08:58.820
as it shines through them,

00:08:58.820 --> 00:09:00.820
it might warm them slightly,

00:09:00.820 --> 00:09:02.820
or it can't really warm them,

00:09:02.820 --> 00:09:04.820
it actually only warms

00:09:04.820 --> 00:09:06.820
the ground-level air layers.

00:09:06.820 --> 00:09:07.820
That's the air layer

00:09:07.820 --> 00:09:09.820
that's really sitting on the ground,

00:09:09.820 --> 00:09:11.820
with the radiation heat

00:09:11.820 --> 00:09:12.820
that arises there,

00:09:12.820 --> 00:09:15.820
and the ground-level air layer warms up.

00:09:15.820 --> 00:09:17.820
And the heating

00:09:17.820 --> 00:09:19.820
of these ground-level air layers

00:09:19.820 --> 00:09:21.820
varies by region around the world,

00:09:21.820 --> 00:09:23.820
distributed across the globe,

00:09:23.820 --> 00:09:25.820
where things warm differently.

00:09:25.820 --> 00:09:27.820
Regions at the equator

00:09:27.820 --> 00:09:29.820
warm up more, of course,

00:09:29.820 --> 00:09:30.820
than a region

00:09:30.820 --> 00:09:31.820
in the polar areas.

00:10:02.300 --> 00:10:04.300
An air mass

00:10:04.300 --> 00:10:06.300
is actually a volume of air

00:10:06.300 --> 00:10:08.300
that has the same properties.

00:10:08.300 --> 00:10:10.300
For example warmer air masses,

00:10:10.300 --> 00:10:12.300
and colder ones.

00:10:12.300 --> 00:10:13.300
And these are always regions

00:10:13.300 --> 00:10:15.300
that, over several hundred kilometres,

00:10:15.300 --> 00:10:17.300
have the same properties,

00:10:17.300 --> 00:10:19.300
so the same air pressure,

00:10:19.300 --> 00:10:20.300
or the same temperature,

00:10:20.300 --> 00:10:21.300
or similar temperatures,

00:10:21.300 --> 00:10:22.300
warmer temperatures

00:10:22.300 --> 00:10:24.300
or colder temperatures.

00:10:27.580 --> 00:10:29.580
Basically, it works like this:

00:10:29.580 --> 00:10:30.580
over regions

00:10:30.580 --> 00:10:32.580
that are colder for longer

00:10:32.580 --> 00:10:34.580
than the surroundings,

00:10:34.580 --> 00:10:37.580
higher air pressure forms.

00:10:37.580 --> 00:10:38.580
And over regions

00:10:38.580 --> 00:10:39.580
that are warm for longer,

00:10:39.580 --> 00:10:41.580
you get

00:10:41.580 --> 00:10:42.580
the formation of

00:10:42.580 --> 00:10:43.580
lower pressure.

00:10:43.580 --> 00:10:45.580
And accordingly,

00:10:45.580 --> 00:10:47.580
in the tropical regions,

00:10:47.580 --> 00:10:49.580
for example, we get tropical low-pressure areas,

00:10:49.580 --> 00:10:51.580
and in the polar regions

00:10:51.580 --> 00:10:53.580
we get the polar high-pressure areas.

00:10:53.580 --> 00:10:56.580
That's how different air pressures form.

00:10:56.580 --> 00:10:59.580
And then the pressure areas develop

00:10:59.580 --> 00:11:02.580
that we'll dive into in the next few slides.

00:11:02.580 --> 00:11:03.580
So,

00:11:03.580 --> 00:11:04.580
that was about

00:11:04.580 --> 00:11:06.580
what kind of influence

00:11:06.580 --> 00:11:08.580
this has on our weather.

00:11:08.580 --> 00:11:09.900
You can picture it

00:11:09.900 --> 00:11:11.900
as belts

00:11:11.900 --> 00:11:12.900
around the world.

00:11:12.900 --> 00:11:13.900
Around the globe,

00:11:13.900 --> 00:11:15.900
there are the so-called Hadley cells,

00:11:15.900 --> 00:11:17.900
they are the low-pressure

00:11:17.900 --> 00:11:18.900
and high-pressure rings.

00:11:18.900 --> 00:11:19.900
There are more of them

00:11:19.900 --> 00:11:20.900
than what's on this graphic.

00:11:20.900 --> 00:11:23.000
Basically though,

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:25.000
in the tropical regions

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:26.000
you get a low-pressure belt

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:27.000
and in the polar regions

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:29.000
a high-pressure belt.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:33.030
And so we also have tropical air masses

00:11:33.030 --> 00:11:35.030
and polar air masses.

00:11:35.030 --> 00:11:37.030
And here too we'll now

00:11:37.030 --> 00:11:39.030
in the next few minutes learn

00:11:39.030 --> 00:11:43.030
what kind of influence that has on our weather.

00:11:43.030 --> 00:11:45.770
So look here,

00:11:45.770 --> 00:11:47.770
there's different heating

00:11:47.770 --> 00:11:49.770
of different regions.

00:11:49.770 --> 00:11:51.770
Accordingly we have high-pressure areas

00:11:51.770 --> 00:11:53.770
and low-pressure areas.

00:11:53.770 --> 00:11:55.770
And we can see here in the middle, for example,

00:11:55.770 --> 00:11:56.770
the number,

00:11:56.770 --> 00:11:57.770
that we can recognise,

00:11:57.770 --> 00:11:59.770
from the standard atmosphere.

00:11:59.770 --> 00:12:02.770
The 1013.25, and as soon as

00:12:02.770 --> 00:12:04.960
the air pressure drops below this.

00:12:04.960 --> 00:12:05.960
Below that,

00:12:05.960 --> 00:12:07.960
we talk about a low-pressure area.

00:12:07.960 --> 00:12:09.960
Here in Europe,

00:12:09.960 --> 00:12:11.960
very pronounced examples

00:12:11.960 --> 00:12:12.960
of low-pressure areas,

00:12:12.960 --> 00:12:15.960
we talk about 955 hectopascals,

00:12:15.960 --> 00:12:17.960
and very pronounced

00:12:17.960 --> 00:12:18.960
high-pressure areas,

00:12:18.960 --> 00:12:21.960
we talk about 1035 hectopascals.

00:12:21.960 --> 00:12:22.960
Right now it's the time

00:12:22.960 --> 00:12:23.960
of global warming.

00:12:23.960 --> 00:12:25.960
Unfortunately, the values

00:12:25.960 --> 00:12:26.960
are getting more extreme.

00:12:26.960 --> 00:12:28.960
There are even high-pressure areas

00:12:28.960 --> 00:12:32.960
that reach up to 1048 hectopascals.

00:12:32.960 --> 00:12:34.960
So those are very strong

00:12:34.960 --> 00:12:36.960
pressure differences.

00:12:36.960 --> 00:12:38.960
Accordingly,

00:12:38.960 --> 00:12:43.960
the

00:12:43.960 --> 00:12:46.960
meteorological phenomena get stronger.

00:12:46.960 --> 00:12:48.960
And the stronger weather,

00:12:48.960 --> 00:12:50.960
that we unfortunately keep experiencing,

00:12:50.960 --> 00:12:54.400
with the storms, for example,

00:12:54.400 --> 00:12:56.620
has exactly to do with these pressure fluctuations,

00:12:56.620 --> 00:12:58.620
and we'll get to it later too,

00:12:58.620 --> 00:13:02.620
in a high-pressure area

00:13:02.620 --> 00:13:04.620
air masses sink,

00:13:04.620 --> 00:13:05.620
and in a low-pressure area

00:13:05.620 --> 00:13:06.620
air masses rise.

00:13:06.620 --> 00:13:08.620
That's very important later

00:13:08.620 --> 00:13:10.620
for flying weather,

00:13:10.620 --> 00:13:12.620
which we'll get to.

00:13:12.620 --> 00:13:13.620
And basically,

00:13:13.620 --> 00:13:15.620
like every gas

00:13:15.620 --> 00:13:17.620
or every liquid,

00:13:17.620 --> 00:13:19.620
air masses have

00:13:19.620 --> 00:13:22.620
the need to equalise pressure.

00:13:22.620 --> 00:13:23.620
That means

00:13:23.620 --> 00:13:25.620
air masses will always

00:13:25.620 --> 00:13:27.620
flow from high pressure to low pressure,

00:13:27.620 --> 00:13:29.620
because pressure wants to equalise.

00:13:29.620 --> 00:13:31.820
And accordingly,

00:13:31.820 --> 00:13:33.820
especially for us when waiting,

00:13:33.820 --> 00:13:35.820
or in the lower air layers,

00:13:35.820 --> 00:13:37.820
the air flow is important,

00:13:37.820 --> 00:13:39.820
that air flows from high

00:13:39.820 --> 00:13:42.820
to low, and accordingly

00:13:42.820 --> 00:13:44.820
wind develops,

00:13:44.820 --> 00:13:45.820
the wind systems

00:13:45.820 --> 00:13:47.820
that you can feel,

00:13:47.820 --> 00:13:49.820
when the wind blows.

00:13:49.820 --> 00:13:51.820
And so we get

00:13:51.820 --> 00:13:53.820
the high-altitude flow,

00:13:53.820 --> 00:13:55.820
which is important for us

00:13:55.820 --> 00:13:57.820
to recognise wind directions

00:13:57.820 --> 00:14:01.000
and read them from the charts.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:04.030
Then we come to isobar charts

00:14:04.030 --> 00:14:05.030
wait,

00:14:05.030 --> 00:14:06.030
you might have heard of those

00:14:06.030 --> 00:14:08.030
or read about them in the theory book.

00:14:08.030 --> 00:14:10.030
There are weather charts

00:14:10.030 --> 00:14:12.030
where exactly the weather phenomena

00:14:12.030 --> 00:14:13.030
that we just

00:14:13.030 --> 00:14:14.030
discussed

00:14:14.030 --> 00:14:15.380
are described.

00:14:15.380 --> 00:14:16.380
Weather charts,

00:14:16.380 --> 00:14:17.380
they're created

00:14:17.380 --> 00:14:19.380
partly from current measurements,

00:14:19.380 --> 00:14:20.380
where you measure with barometers

00:14:20.380 --> 00:14:22.380
or air pressure.

00:14:22.380 --> 00:14:25.380
And of course the computer models,

00:14:25.380 --> 00:14:27.380
that based on the measurements

00:14:27.380 --> 00:14:28.380
try to predict

00:14:28.380 --> 00:14:30.380
the weather,

00:14:30.380 --> 00:14:31.180
and

00:14:31.180 --> 00:14:32.380
compute it in advance.

00:14:32.380 --> 00:14:34.380
And then come

00:14:34.380 --> 00:14:35.380
the funny-looking weather charts,

00:14:35.380 --> 00:14:37.380
which we'll now look at more closely,

00:14:37.380 --> 00:14:40.380
how to read them.

00:14:40.380 --> 00:14:42.380
Isobar charts,

00:14:42.380 --> 00:14:44.380
isobars,

00:14:44.380 --> 00:14:45.380
those are the lines

00:14:45.380 --> 00:14:47.740
you see there,

00:14:47.740 --> 00:14:49.740
isobars,

00:14:49.740 --> 00:14:50.740
described,

00:14:50.740 --> 00:14:51.740
are the regions

00:14:51.740 --> 00:14:52.740
that have the same air pressure,

00:14:52.740 --> 00:14:53.740
or the same air pressure,

00:14:53.740 --> 00:14:55.740
simply put,

00:14:55.740 --> 00:14:56.800
where it prevails.

00:14:56.800 --> 00:14:58.800
So for example,

00:14:58.800 --> 00:14:59.800
1025 hectopascals,

00:14:59.800 --> 00:15:01.800
you can't see it well here,

00:15:01.800 --> 00:15:02.800
in the next chart

00:15:02.800 --> 00:15:03.800
you can see it better.

00:15:03.800 --> 00:15:04.800
And everywhere

00:15:04.800 --> 00:15:05.800
the lines run,

00:15:05.800 --> 00:15:07.800
calculated at sea level,

00:15:07.800 --> 00:15:08.800
that's very important,

00:15:08.800 --> 00:15:10.800
the pressure is calculated

00:15:10.800 --> 00:15:11.800
at sea level,

00:15:11.800 --> 00:15:13.800
where the same air pressure prevails.

00:15:13.800 --> 00:15:16.800
That's where the name isobar chart comes from.

00:15:16.800 --> 00:15:17.800
Iso means the same,

00:15:17.800 --> 00:15:18.800
bar

00:15:18.800 --> 00:15:19.800
is pressure,

00:15:19.800 --> 00:15:20.800
everywhere

00:15:20.800 --> 00:15:21.800
where the same air pressure prevails,

00:15:21.800 --> 00:15:23.800
such a line gets drawn.

00:15:23.800 --> 00:15:26.410
And on such an isobar chart

00:15:26.410 --> 00:15:28.410
fronts are often drawn in,

00:15:28.410 --> 00:15:29.410
naturally,

00:15:29.410 --> 00:15:30.410
we'll come back to that later

00:15:30.410 --> 00:15:32.410
in the course,

00:15:32.410 --> 00:15:34.540
what these fronts

00:15:34.540 --> 00:15:36.860
are about.

00:15:36.860 --> 00:15:38.860
Here you see a larger isobar chart,

00:15:38.860 --> 00:15:40.860
and you see again the high-pressure areas,

00:15:40.860 --> 00:15:41.860
the low-pressure areas,

00:15:41.860 --> 00:15:42.860
and there are reasons

00:15:42.860 --> 00:15:44.860
why different air pressures form,

00:15:44.860 --> 00:15:46.860
to keep in mind,

00:15:46.860 --> 00:15:49.860
and the season for example.

00:15:49.860 --> 00:15:53.240
This is a slightly larger view

00:15:53.240 --> 00:15:54.240
of an isobar chart.

00:15:54.240 --> 00:15:55.240
Their appearance

00:15:55.240 --> 00:15:56.240
varies a bit,

00:15:56.240 --> 00:15:58.240
depending on the newspaper,

00:15:58.240 --> 00:15:59.240
or by which meteo service,

00:15:59.240 --> 00:16:01.240
looks a bit different,

00:16:01.240 --> 00:16:03.240
but fundamentally they all have

00:16:03.240 --> 00:16:04.240
the same elements in them.

00:16:04.240 --> 00:16:06.240
Those are the high-pressure areas,

00:16:06.240 --> 00:16:07.240
isobars,

00:16:07.240 --> 00:16:09.240
and the coloured lines,

00:16:09.240 --> 00:16:14.220
the fronts.

00:16:14.220 --> 00:16:15.410
Right.

00:16:15.410 --> 00:16:16.410
So here's what it looks like,

00:16:16.410 --> 00:16:18.410
we've just simply shown

00:16:18.410 --> 00:16:20.410
on our globe,

00:16:20.410 --> 00:16:21.410
the different pressure areas

00:16:21.410 --> 00:16:22.410
that form,

00:16:22.410 --> 00:16:25.410
over different land masses and seas.

00:16:25.410 --> 00:16:26.410
They have different pressures,

00:16:26.410 --> 00:16:28.410
and different pressure values.

00:16:28.410 --> 00:16:32.630
And the Coriolis force,

00:16:32.630 --> 00:16:35.700
that's a physical phenomenon,

00:16:35.700 --> 00:16:37.700
Earth's rotation,

00:16:37.700 --> 00:16:40.700
deflects different

00:16:40.700 --> 00:16:42.700
air masses,

00:16:42.700 --> 00:16:43.700
that get moving,

00:16:43.700 --> 00:16:45.700
differently,

00:16:45.700 --> 00:16:47.700
and these create

00:16:47.700 --> 00:16:49.700
circular motions,

00:16:49.700 --> 00:16:51.700
so rotating movements,

00:16:51.700 --> 00:16:54.700
to put it visually,

00:16:54.700 --> 00:16:56.700
like a drain for example,

00:16:56.700 --> 00:16:58.700
different forces arise,

00:16:58.700 --> 00:17:00.700
or the shape of a drain,

00:17:00.700 --> 00:17:01.700
creates a vortex,

00:17:01.700 --> 00:17:04.700
when water flows down a drain

00:17:04.700 --> 00:17:06.700
and starts to rotate,

00:17:06.700 --> 00:17:09.700
and that creates a rotating motion.

00:17:09.700 --> 00:17:12.700
In air masses, the Coriolis force is mainly

00:17:12.700 --> 00:17:13.700
the deciding factor,

00:17:13.700 --> 00:17:15.700
that air masses

00:17:15.700 --> 00:17:17.700
also start to rotate.

00:17:17.700 --> 00:17:20.980
Accordingly in the north,

00:17:20.980 --> 00:17:23.980
of our globe,

00:17:23.980 --> 00:17:24.980
so everything north

00:17:24.980 --> 00:17:26.980
of the equator,

00:17:26.980 --> 00:17:27.980
it works like this:

00:17:27.980 --> 00:17:29.980
in a high-pressure area

00:17:29.980 --> 00:17:32.980
the air masses rotate clockwise,

00:17:32.980 --> 00:17:34.980
and in a low-pressure area

00:17:34.980 --> 00:17:36.980
counter-clockwise.

00:17:36.980 --> 00:17:38.980
I've built myself a little memory aid here:

00:17:38.980 --> 00:17:40.980
for me a high-pressure area

00:17:40.980 --> 00:17:41.980
is something positive,

00:17:41.980 --> 00:17:43.980
because the sun shines on us

00:17:43.980 --> 00:17:45.980
and we have nice weather, flying weather.

00:17:45.980 --> 00:17:47.980
So it's positive,

00:17:47.980 --> 00:17:49.980
and for me that means clockwise,

00:17:49.980 --> 00:17:51.980
in a low-pressure area

00:17:51.980 --> 00:17:53.980
counter-clockwise.

00:17:53.980 --> 00:17:55.980
The rotation.

00:17:55.980 --> 00:17:57.980
In the southern hemisphere

00:17:57.980 --> 00:17:58.980
it's the opposite,

00:17:58.980 --> 00:18:00.980
for example in Australia,

00:18:00.980 --> 00:18:03.110
the whole thing works exactly

00:18:03.110 --> 00:18:04.110
opposite,

00:18:04.110 --> 00:18:05.110
just for those

00:18:05.110 --> 00:18:06.110
who go on flying trips

00:18:06.110 --> 00:18:08.110
and fly in South America

00:18:08.110 --> 00:18:09.110
or Australia

00:18:09.110 --> 00:18:11.110
it's reversed.

00:18:11.110 --> 00:18:13.110
Quite nicely,

00:18:13.110 --> 00:18:15.110
in a low-pressure area

00:18:15.110 --> 00:18:19.520
in a low-pressure area

00:18:19.520 --> 00:18:21.520
is of course also naturally

00:18:21.520 --> 00:18:23.520
the case with a hurricane.

00:18:23.520 --> 00:18:24.520
There you can really see

00:18:24.520 --> 00:18:26.520
how the air mass rotates.

00:18:26.520 --> 00:18:27.520
A hurricane

00:18:27.520 --> 00:18:28.520
is nothing other

00:18:28.520 --> 00:18:31.520
than an extreme low-pressure area.

00:18:31.520 --> 00:18:33.520
Accordingly you can see,

00:18:33.520 --> 00:18:34.520
this is a hurricane,

00:18:34.520 --> 00:18:36.520
it's in the northern

00:18:36.520 --> 00:18:37.520
hemisphere,

00:18:37.520 --> 00:18:38.520
you can see again

00:18:38.520 --> 00:18:39.520
counter-clockwise,

00:18:39.520 --> 00:18:42.520
rotating in the low-pressure area

00:18:42.520 --> 00:18:44.520
in such a way.

00:18:44.520 --> 00:18:46.520
The air masses.

00:18:46.520 --> 00:18:47.520
You can see very nicely

00:18:47.520 --> 00:18:49.520
on the cloud bands

00:18:49.520 --> 00:18:52.640
of the hurricane.

00:18:52.640 --> 00:18:53.640
Accordingly,

00:18:53.640 --> 00:18:55.640
on this slide,

00:18:55.640 --> 00:18:56.640
you can see

00:18:56.640 --> 00:18:57.640
that the air masses

00:18:57.640 --> 00:18:58.640
equalise the low pressure,

00:18:58.640 --> 00:18:59.640
they flow from high pressure

00:18:59.640 --> 00:19:01.640
into the low-pressure area.

00:19:01.640 --> 00:19:02.640
But they don't flow

00:19:02.640 --> 00:19:04.640
in a direct line

00:19:04.640 --> 00:19:06.640
from high to low,

00:19:18.640 --> 00:19:21.900
but in a curve into the low-pressure area.

00:19:21.900 --> 00:19:28.020
About wind direction.

00:19:28.020 --> 00:19:30.020
Reading it

00:19:30.020 --> 00:19:32.020
we'll look at on the charts.

00:19:32.020 --> 00:19:33.020
We'll look at that

00:19:33.020 --> 00:19:35.020
in a few slides,

00:19:35.020 --> 00:19:36.020
how to read wind direction

00:19:36.020 --> 00:19:39.280
on the isobar charts.

00:19:39.280 --> 00:19:41.630
We can also read wind speed

00:19:41.630 --> 00:19:42.630
from

00:19:42.630 --> 00:19:44.630
these isobar charts

00:19:44.630 --> 00:19:45.630
by

00:19:45.630 --> 00:19:46.630
to put it visually

00:19:46.630 --> 00:19:48.630
comparing isobar charts.

00:19:48.630 --> 00:19:50.630
I can also always

00:19:50.630 --> 00:19:52.630
read them a bit like topographic maps.

00:19:52.630 --> 00:19:54.630
So there are different elevation lines,

00:19:54.630 --> 00:19:55.630
different pressure lines

00:19:55.630 --> 00:19:56.630
and accordingly

00:19:56.630 --> 00:19:58.630
I have for example

00:19:58.630 --> 00:19:59.630
a high-pressure area

00:19:59.630 --> 00:20:01.630
of varying heights.

00:20:01.630 --> 00:20:02.630
A high pressure

00:20:02.630 --> 00:20:03.630
and its influence accordingly

00:20:03.630 --> 00:20:05.630
is of varying strength,

00:20:05.630 --> 00:20:07.630
you can think of it as a 4000-metre peak

00:20:07.630 --> 00:20:09.630
of high pressure.

00:20:09.630 --> 00:20:10.630
That's extremely strong.

00:20:10.630 --> 00:20:12.630
There are very many isobar lines,

00:20:12.630 --> 00:20:14.630
very many topographic lines

00:20:14.630 --> 00:20:16.630
from the landscape.

00:20:16.630 --> 00:20:18.630
Or it can also be just a hill.

00:20:18.630 --> 00:20:20.630
But the high

00:20:20.630 --> 00:20:22.630
actually only describes the highest pressure,

00:20:22.630 --> 00:20:24.630
so the highest elevation

00:20:24.630 --> 00:20:25.630
of the landscape

00:20:25.630 --> 00:20:27.630
or of the hill.

00:20:27.630 --> 00:20:28.630
And accordingly

00:20:28.630 --> 00:20:29.630
it can be higher

00:20:29.630 --> 00:20:30.630
or less high.

00:20:30.630 --> 00:20:31.920
And accordingly

00:20:31.920 --> 00:20:33.920
the weather influences,

00:20:33.920 --> 00:20:35.920
that we'll discuss in a bit,

00:20:35.920 --> 00:20:37.920
are stronger or weaker.

00:20:37.920 --> 00:20:40.710
Let's talk about,

00:20:40.710 --> 00:20:42.710
let's now quickly look at,

00:20:42.710 --> 00:20:44.710
how from an isobar chart

00:20:44.710 --> 00:20:46.900
you can read off wind direction.

00:20:46.900 --> 00:20:48.900
Basically we have,

00:20:48.900 --> 00:20:50.900
here's an infographic

00:20:50.900 --> 00:20:52.900
from the theory exam.

00:20:52.900 --> 00:20:54.940
We've now seen different pressure areas

00:20:54.940 --> 00:20:55.940
before.

00:20:55.940 --> 00:20:57.940
The exam doesn't make it

00:20:57.940 --> 00:20:58.940
that simple,

00:20:58.940 --> 00:21:00.940
where an H and a T

00:21:00.940 --> 00:21:01.940
are put in.

00:21:01.940 --> 00:21:02.940
And then we know

00:21:02.940 --> 00:21:03.940
what the pressure area is.

00:21:03.940 --> 00:21:04.940
Accordingly they want

00:21:04.940 --> 00:21:05.940
us,

00:21:05.940 --> 00:21:06.940
to read the pressure

00:21:06.940 --> 00:21:07.940
from the isobars

00:21:07.940 --> 00:21:08.940
and we see for example,

00:21:08.940 --> 00:21:10.940
at the edge in Navier above,

00:21:10.940 --> 00:21:12.940
you see 900,

00:21:12.940 --> 00:21:14.940
it's relatively hard to read.

00:21:14.940 --> 00:21:16.940
980 hectopascals for example,

00:21:16.940 --> 00:21:17.940
you know

00:21:17.940 --> 00:21:19.940
that's below 1013.25.

00:21:19.940 --> 00:21:21.940
So it must be low pressure.

00:21:21.940 --> 00:21:22.940
Accordingly you can

00:21:22.940 --> 00:21:23.940
in your mind

00:21:23.940 --> 00:21:24.940
write the T

00:21:24.940 --> 00:21:25.940
where it would be,

00:21:25.940 --> 00:21:26.940
in there.

00:21:26.940 --> 00:21:28.940
Accordingly we know

00:21:28.940 --> 00:21:29.940
that the air masses

00:21:29.940 --> 00:21:31.940
in the low-pressure area

00:21:31.940 --> 00:21:32.940
rotate counter-clockwise.

00:21:32.940 --> 00:21:33.940
Rotating.

00:21:33.940 --> 00:21:36.290
And then you can

00:21:36.290 --> 00:21:37.290
along the isobar lines,

00:21:37.290 --> 00:21:38.290
that you see,

00:21:38.290 --> 00:21:39.290
you can,

00:21:39.290 --> 00:21:40.290
if you want,

00:21:40.290 --> 00:21:41.290
draw little arrows,

00:21:41.290 --> 00:21:42.290
or you can of course

00:21:42.290 --> 00:21:43.290
just visualise it,

00:21:43.290 --> 00:21:45.290
you can imagine

00:21:45.290 --> 00:21:47.290
many arrows along the isobar lines,

00:21:47.290 --> 00:21:48.290
depicted,

00:21:48.290 --> 00:21:49.290
and there it is,

00:21:49.290 --> 00:21:50.480
if you imagine,

00:21:50.480 --> 00:21:51.480
and accordingly

00:21:51.480 --> 00:21:53.480
you read off the wind direction.

00:21:53.480 --> 00:21:54.480
So here for example

00:21:54.480 --> 00:21:56.480
in England

00:21:56.480 --> 00:21:58.480
you'd always have a westerly flow.

00:21:58.480 --> 00:22:00.510
And in the high-pressure area,

00:22:00.510 --> 00:22:02.510
at 1030 hecto-

00:22:02.510 --> 00:22:03.510
pascals,

00:22:03.510 --> 00:22:04.510
we have the highest elevation.

00:22:04.510 --> 00:22:05.510
That's the high,

00:22:05.510 --> 00:22:06.510
it rotates

00:22:06.510 --> 00:22:07.510
clockwise.

00:22:07.510 --> 00:22:09.510
Accordingly

00:22:09.510 --> 00:22:10.510
the wind goes

00:22:10.510 --> 00:22:12.510
along the isobars.

00:22:12.510 --> 00:22:13.510
And then we can really

00:22:13.510 --> 00:22:14.510
for the theory exam,

00:22:14.510 --> 00:22:15.510
say that the wind is always

00:22:15.510 --> 00:22:16.510
parallel to the isobars

00:22:16.510 --> 00:22:17.510
and gets read off.

00:22:17.510 --> 00:22:18.510
So we really take

00:22:18.510 --> 00:22:19.510
the line

00:22:19.510 --> 00:22:20.510
as the wind direction.

00:22:20.510 --> 00:22:21.510
Because the wind

00:22:21.510 --> 00:22:23.960
is a circulating

00:22:23.960 --> 00:22:24.960
motion that equalises

00:22:24.960 --> 00:22:25.960
out,

00:22:25.960 --> 00:22:27.600
the pressure.

00:22:27.600 --> 00:22:30.270
Right.

00:22:30.270 --> 00:22:31.270
So that's for wind direction

00:22:31.270 --> 00:22:32.270
and wind direction.

00:22:32.270 --> 00:22:33.270
I could also

00:22:33.270 --> 00:22:34.270
ask,

00:22:34.270 --> 00:22:35.270
for example,

00:22:35.270 --> 00:22:36.270
as the high and low-pressure area,

00:22:36.270 --> 00:22:38.270
as a connected system function.

00:22:38.270 --> 00:22:39.270
Yes, we can

00:22:39.270 --> 00:22:40.270
imagine,

00:22:40.270 --> 00:22:41.270
like two gears,

00:22:41.270 --> 00:22:42.270
that mesh with each other

00:22:42.270 --> 00:22:43.270
and accordingly

00:22:43.270 --> 00:22:44.270
the wind

00:22:44.270 --> 00:22:45.270
it has to also

00:22:45.270 --> 00:22:46.270
ask better,

00:22:46.270 --> 00:22:47.270
maybe.

00:22:47.270 --> 00:22:48.270
Right.

00:22:48.270 --> 00:22:49.270
When reading wind,

00:22:49.270 --> 00:22:50.270
we'll now look

00:22:50.270 --> 00:22:52.270
at the next few slides.

00:22:52.270 --> 00:22:53.270
One thing

00:22:53.270 --> 00:22:54.270
that's of

00:22:54.270 --> 00:22:55.270
great importance for wind

00:22:55.270 --> 00:22:56.270
is,

00:22:56.270 --> 00:22:57.270
wind direction.

00:22:57.270 --> 00:22:58.270
We need to know,

00:22:58.270 --> 00:22:59.270
because we need to know wind direction

00:22:59.270 --> 00:23:00.270
for example,

00:23:00.270 --> 00:23:01.270
for which launch site to use.

00:23:01.270 --> 00:23:02.270
Wind direction is also

00:23:02.270 --> 00:23:04.270
important for different weather phenomena.

00:23:04.270 --> 00:23:05.270
You can

00:23:05.270 --> 00:23:06.270
imagine,

00:23:06.270 --> 00:23:07.270
pull out a compass.

00:23:07.270 --> 00:23:09.270
With north at 0 degrees,

00:23:09.270 --> 00:23:10.270
east at 90 degrees,

00:23:10.270 --> 00:23:12.270
south at 180 degrees,

00:23:12.270 --> 00:23:14.270
west at 270 degrees.

00:23:14.270 --> 00:23:15.270
Accordingly

00:23:15.270 --> 00:23:16.270
wind direction

00:23:16.270 --> 00:23:17.270
is sometimes also

00:23:17.270 --> 00:23:18.270
given

00:23:18.270 --> 00:23:20.270
in 360 degrees.

00:23:20.270 --> 00:23:22.850
Wind direction is always described

00:23:22.850 --> 00:23:24.850
by where the wind is coming from.

00:23:24.850 --> 00:23:25.850
So if the wind

00:23:25.850 --> 00:23:26.850
comes from the south,

00:23:26.850 --> 00:23:27.850
then we talk about south wind,

00:23:27.850 --> 00:23:28.850
north wind

00:23:28.850 --> 00:23:29.850
and west wind,

00:23:29.850 --> 00:23:30.850
accordingly with

00:23:30.850 --> 00:23:31.850
ground air mass

00:23:31.850 --> 00:23:32.850
from the west

00:23:32.850 --> 00:23:33.850
and accordingly

00:23:33.850 --> 00:23:34.850
is west wind.

00:23:34.850 --> 00:23:36.850
And accordingly

00:23:36.850 --> 00:23:38.850
we also give as,

00:23:38.850 --> 00:23:39.850
so when you have wind

00:23:39.850 --> 00:23:40.850
from 90 degrees

00:24:30.030 --> 00:24:32.030
is a bit the

00:24:32.030 --> 00:24:34.030
common unit

00:24:34.030 --> 00:24:35.030
for wind speed.

00:24:35.030 --> 00:24:36.030
We can roughly,

00:24:36.030 --> 00:24:37.030
in most

00:24:37.030 --> 00:24:39.030
weather stations for example

00:24:39.030 --> 00:24:41.030
the wind is given that way.

00:24:41.030 --> 00:24:42.160
And here

00:24:42.160 --> 00:24:43.160
another natural

00:24:43.160 --> 00:24:44.160
second example,

00:24:44.160 --> 00:24:45.160
20 degrees.

00:24:45.160 --> 00:24:46.160
Times 2,

00:24:46.160 --> 00:24:47.160
40,

00:24:47.160 --> 00:24:48.160
minus 6,

00:24:48.160 --> 00:24:49.160
that's 4,

00:24:49.160 --> 00:24:50.160
so it gives

00:24:50.160 --> 00:24:51.160
360-degree

00:24:51.160 --> 00:24:52.290
wind.

00:24:52.290 --> 00:24:53.290
Converting it

00:24:53.290 --> 00:24:54.290
is important,

00:24:54.290 --> 00:24:55.290
so we're fluent

00:24:55.290 --> 00:24:56.290
and prepared

00:24:56.290 --> 00:24:57.290
for the theory exam.

00:24:57.290 --> 00:25:00.310
Then if you also

00:25:00.310 --> 00:25:02.310
look at the wind topic

00:25:02.310 --> 00:25:03.310
one more,

00:25:03.310 --> 00:25:05.340
the wind gradient.

00:25:05.340 --> 00:25:06.340
If you imagine

00:25:06.340 --> 00:25:07.340
now,

00:25:07.340 --> 00:25:08.340
that my circulating

00:25:08.340 --> 00:25:09.340
wind system comes,

00:25:09.340 --> 00:25:10.340
with a westerly wind,

00:25:10.340 --> 00:25:11.340
and it glides

00:25:11.340 --> 00:25:12.340
over the Earth's

00:25:12.340 --> 00:25:13.340
surface.

00:25:13.340 --> 00:25:17.340
Accordingly the wind

00:25:17.340 --> 00:25:18.340
wind at altitude

00:25:18.340 --> 00:25:19.340
is mostly stronger.

00:25:19.340 --> 00:25:20.340
At ground level

00:25:20.340 --> 00:25:21.340
the wind has friction.

00:25:21.340 --> 00:25:22.340
Accordingly it gets

00:25:22.340 --> 00:25:23.340
slower,

00:25:23.340 --> 00:25:24.340
but it also becomes

00:25:24.340 --> 00:25:25.340
a bit turbulent.

00:25:25.340 --> 00:25:26.340
So accordingly

00:25:26.340 --> 00:25:27.340
there are

00:25:27.340 --> 00:25:28.340
some ground rules,

00:25:28.340 --> 00:25:30.340
that in the thin layer

00:25:30.340 --> 00:25:31.340
the ground-level layer

00:25:31.340 --> 00:25:32.340
the wind is weaker,

00:25:32.340 --> 00:25:33.340
but turbulent.

00:25:33.340 --> 00:25:35.340
And in higher air layers

00:25:35.340 --> 00:25:36.340
it's stronger,

00:25:36.340 --> 00:25:37.340
but laminar.

00:25:37.340 --> 00:25:39.340
Logically there are

00:25:39.340 --> 00:25:40.340
still different

00:25:40.340 --> 00:25:41.340
meteorological phenomena,

00:25:41.340 --> 00:25:42.340
where, yes,

00:25:42.340 --> 00:25:43.340
maybe sometimes

00:25:43.340 --> 00:25:44.340
a bit turbulent

00:25:44.340 --> 00:25:45.340
in the air mass

00:25:45.340 --> 00:25:46.340
at higher altitudes,

00:25:46.340 --> 00:25:47.340
or the whole thing also

00:25:47.340 --> 00:25:48.340
acts a bit oddly.

00:25:48.340 --> 00:25:49.340
But as a basic principle

00:25:49.340 --> 00:25:50.340
it goes like this,

00:25:50.340 --> 00:25:51.340
if you know the wind flow,

00:25:51.340 --> 00:25:52.340
at the ground it's

00:25:52.340 --> 00:25:54.340
weaker and turbulent.

00:25:54.340 --> 00:25:55.340
Right.

00:25:55.340 --> 00:25:57.340
The wind gradient.

00:25:57.340 --> 00:25:59.340
By the way, a gradient

00:25:59.340 --> 00:26:00.340
is always a progression,

00:26:00.340 --> 00:26:01.340
in this sense

00:26:01.340 --> 00:26:02.340
with altitude.

00:26:02.340 --> 00:26:04.340
So temperature gradient

00:26:04.340 --> 00:26:06.340
later in the theory course,

00:26:06.340 --> 00:26:07.340
it's always about

00:26:07.340 --> 00:26:09.340
a progression

00:26:09.340 --> 00:26:10.340
with altitude.

00:26:10.340 --> 00:26:12.340
When we talk about a gradient,

00:26:12.340 --> 00:26:14.340
in general,

00:26:14.340 --> 00:26:15.340
but in meteorology

00:26:15.340 --> 00:26:16.380
it's mainly about altitude.

00:26:16.380 --> 00:26:18.300
Right.

00:26:18.300 --> 00:26:20.300
On the topic of wind, there's

00:26:20.300 --> 00:26:21.300
another topic that belongs with it,

00:26:21.300 --> 00:26:22.300
that for us paraglider pilots

00:26:22.300 --> 00:26:23.300
is especially important

00:26:23.300 --> 00:26:24.300
and that's turbulence.

00:26:24.300 --> 00:26:25.300
If you want

00:26:25.300 --> 00:26:26.300
the most peaceful flight possible,

00:26:26.300 --> 00:26:27.300
the perspective,

00:26:27.300 --> 00:26:28.300
when you're in turbulence,

00:26:28.300 --> 00:26:29.300
you'd want to know,

00:26:29.300 --> 00:26:30.300
and know why

00:26:30.300 --> 00:26:31.300
this turbulence forms.

00:26:31.300 --> 00:26:33.300
And how to

00:26:33.300 --> 00:26:34.300
deal with it,

00:26:34.300 --> 00:26:35.300
maybe see it a bit beforehand

00:26:35.300 --> 00:26:36.300
and the areas

00:26:36.300 --> 00:26:37.300
that you fly into

00:26:37.300 --> 00:26:38.300
and maybe don't.

00:26:38.300 --> 00:26:39.300
And here it's

00:26:39.300 --> 00:26:40.300
going back

00:26:40.300 --> 00:26:41.800
to types of

00:26:41.800 --> 00:26:42.800
turbulence,

00:26:42.800 --> 00:26:43.800
that we distinguish,

00:26:43.800 --> 00:26:44.800
and which are also tested in the theory exam,

00:26:44.800 --> 00:26:45.800
asked about.

00:26:45.800 --> 00:26:47.340
First there's

00:26:47.340 --> 00:26:48.340
the best turbulence,

00:26:48.340 --> 00:26:49.340
actually,

00:26:49.340 --> 00:26:50.340
definitely pleasant,

00:26:50.340 --> 00:26:51.340
but maybe also less pleasant,

00:26:51.340 --> 00:26:52.840
thermic turbulence.

00:26:52.840 --> 00:26:53.840
That's probably the one

00:26:53.840 --> 00:26:55.340
we're most exposed to

00:26:55.340 --> 00:26:56.340
are,

00:26:56.340 --> 00:26:57.340
when flying,

00:26:57.340 --> 00:26:58.340
because the thermals we fly,

00:26:58.340 --> 00:26:59.340
that we move accordingly,

00:26:59.340 --> 00:27:00.340
are always in thermic

00:27:00.340 --> 00:27:01.340
air masses.

00:27:01.340 --> 00:27:02.340
And those

00:27:02.340 --> 00:27:03.340
who have felt it already,

00:27:03.340 --> 00:27:04.340
know,

00:27:04.340 --> 00:27:05.340
use them well.

00:27:05.340 --> 00:27:06.340
And so it's about,

00:27:06.340 --> 00:27:08.340
when an air mass rises,

00:27:08.340 --> 00:27:09.340
the air mass is

00:27:09.340 --> 00:27:10.340
basically

00:27:10.340 --> 00:27:11.340
relatively calm,

00:27:11.340 --> 00:27:12.340
it sits there

00:27:12.340 --> 00:27:14.340
and then the thermic

00:27:14.340 --> 00:27:15.340
bubble rises up,

00:27:15.340 --> 00:27:16.340
which we'll later

00:27:16.340 --> 00:27:17.340
go into in detail

00:27:17.340 --> 00:27:19.340
and in this rising zone

00:27:19.340 --> 00:27:20.340
there are also often

00:27:20.340 --> 00:27:21.340
next to it,

00:27:21.340 --> 00:27:22.340
a neighbouring downdraft zone

00:27:22.340 --> 00:27:23.340
next to thermic updrafts.

00:27:23.340 --> 00:27:24.340
Accordingly

00:27:24.340 --> 00:27:25.340
you get there

00:27:25.340 --> 00:27:26.340
wind shear

00:27:26.340 --> 00:27:27.340
in the vertical

00:27:27.340 --> 00:27:29.340
and in this wind shear

00:27:29.340 --> 00:27:30.340
you of course feel

00:27:30.340 --> 00:27:31.340
the turbulence.

00:27:31.340 --> 00:27:32.340
Accordingly

00:27:32.340 --> 00:27:34.430
thermic turbulence.

00:27:34.430 --> 00:27:35.430
Then there's

00:27:35.430 --> 00:27:36.430
wind shear

00:27:36.430 --> 00:27:37.430
in this sense.

00:27:37.430 --> 00:27:38.430
That's something,

00:27:38.430 --> 00:27:39.430
it's about,

00:27:39.430 --> 00:27:40.430
when you have two different

00:27:40.430 --> 00:27:41.430
wind directions,

00:27:41.430 --> 00:27:42.690
when you have a westerly down low

00:27:42.690 --> 00:27:43.690
and easterly up high,

00:27:43.690 --> 00:27:45.690
or usually the reverse,

00:27:45.690 --> 00:27:46.690
or you have

00:27:46.690 --> 00:27:47.690
a Bise in there,

00:27:47.690 --> 00:27:48.690
so easterly wind,

00:27:48.690 --> 00:27:49.690
and westerly up high,

00:27:49.690 --> 00:27:51.690
then there's, in the middle,

00:27:51.690 --> 00:27:53.690
a mixing layer,

00:27:53.690 --> 00:27:54.690
where the two wind systems

00:27:54.690 --> 00:27:55.690
meet

00:27:55.690 --> 00:27:56.690
and accordingly

00:27:56.690 --> 00:27:57.690
you get exactly

00:27:57.690 --> 00:27:58.690
at this altitude line,

00:27:58.690 --> 00:28:00.690
where the winds meet,

00:28:00.690 --> 00:28:02.690
so-called shear wind,

00:28:02.690 --> 00:28:03.690
and then it brings

00:28:03.690 --> 00:28:04.690
with it the turbulence,

00:28:04.690 --> 00:28:05.690
or rather

00:28:05.690 --> 00:28:06.690
into the turbulence,

00:28:06.690 --> 00:28:07.690
the turbulence,

00:28:07.690 --> 00:28:09.520
due to wind strength.

00:28:09.520 --> 00:28:10.520
For us as

00:28:10.520 --> 00:28:11.520
pilots

00:28:11.520 --> 00:28:12.520
this isn't that relevant,

00:28:12.520 --> 00:28:13.520
often,

00:28:13.520 --> 00:28:14.520
but it's a phenomenon,

00:28:14.520 --> 00:28:15.520
that there's such a layer,

00:28:15.520 --> 00:28:16.520
where things get bumpy,

00:28:16.520 --> 00:28:17.520
that often has to do with mountain wind,

00:28:17.520 --> 00:28:18.520
for example,

00:28:18.520 --> 00:28:19.520
which we'll also

00:28:19.520 --> 00:28:20.520
come to later.

00:28:20.520 --> 00:28:23.740
With mechanical

00:28:23.740 --> 00:28:24.740
turbulence,

00:28:24.740 --> 00:28:25.740
that's the third

00:28:25.740 --> 00:28:26.740
category,

00:28:26.740 --> 00:28:27.740
it's about exactly,

00:28:27.740 --> 00:28:29.740
when an air mass

00:28:29.740 --> 00:28:30.740
flows over an object,

00:28:30.740 --> 00:28:31.740
for example a forest,

00:28:31.740 --> 00:28:32.740
or a house,

00:28:32.740 --> 00:28:33.740
or anything,

00:28:33.740 --> 00:28:34.740
or even

00:28:34.740 --> 00:28:35.740
most importantly for us

00:28:35.740 --> 00:28:36.740
of relevance,

00:28:36.740 --> 00:28:37.740
a mountain,

00:28:37.740 --> 00:28:38.740
a ridge for example,

00:28:38.740 --> 00:28:39.740
when you have strong wind

00:28:39.740 --> 00:28:42.740
and it flows over the object.

00:28:42.740 --> 00:28:43.740
Many know

00:28:43.740 --> 00:28:44.740
this from all

00:28:44.740 --> 00:28:45.740
those flow videos,

00:28:45.740 --> 00:28:46.740
for them,

00:28:46.740 --> 00:28:47.740
we have a car in a wind tunnel,

00:28:47.740 --> 00:28:48.740
afterwards there are

00:28:48.740 --> 00:28:50.740
behind the object

00:28:50.740 --> 00:28:51.740
vortices,

00:28:51.740 --> 00:28:53.740
which can be unpleasant

00:28:53.740 --> 00:28:54.740
could be,

00:28:54.740 --> 00:28:55.740
of course depending on wind speed,

00:28:55.740 --> 00:28:56.740
they could be unpleasant

00:28:56.740 --> 00:28:57.740
be,

00:28:57.740 --> 00:28:58.740
or even dangerous,

00:28:58.740 --> 00:28:59.740
if the wind is

00:28:59.740 --> 00:29:00.740
weak though,

00:29:00.740 --> 00:29:01.740
then the amounts

00:29:01.740 --> 00:29:02.740
are completely negligible.

00:29:02.740 --> 00:29:03.740
On the landing site

00:29:03.740 --> 00:29:04.740
it's of course

00:29:04.740 --> 00:29:05.740
important,

00:29:05.740 --> 00:29:06.740
if you

00:29:06.740 --> 00:29:07.740
land behind the house,

00:29:07.740 --> 00:29:09.740
when you have strong wind,

00:29:09.740 --> 00:29:10.740
is of course

00:29:10.740 --> 00:29:11.740
not so advantageous.

00:29:11.740 --> 00:29:13.740
Maybe a couple more words,

00:29:13.740 --> 00:29:15.740
that come up again and again,

00:29:15.740 --> 00:29:16.740
when flying,

00:29:16.740 --> 00:29:18.860
is windward and lee.

00:29:18.860 --> 00:29:19.860
The topic,

00:29:19.860 --> 00:29:20.860
that we're on right now,

00:29:20.860 --> 00:29:21.860
is,

00:29:21.860 --> 00:29:22.860
the lee side

00:29:22.860 --> 00:29:23.860
always describes the wind-

00:29:23.860 --> 00:29:25.860
away side.

00:29:25.860 --> 00:29:26.860
And the windward side

00:29:26.860 --> 00:29:28.860
is the wind-facing side.

00:29:28.860 --> 00:29:30.860
Now it's always asked,

00:29:30.860 --> 00:29:31.860
from where do we look at it,

00:29:31.860 --> 00:29:32.860
do we look,

00:29:32.860 --> 00:29:33.860
do we look,

00:29:33.860 --> 00:29:35.860
do we look from an object.

00:29:35.860 --> 00:29:36.860
Or,

00:29:36.860 --> 00:29:37.860
we can also,

00:29:37.860 --> 00:29:38.860
we can,

00:29:38.860 --> 00:29:39.860
for example at the launch site

00:29:39.860 --> 00:29:40.860
talk about the mountain ridge.

00:29:40.860 --> 00:29:42.860
Then we have the lee side,

00:29:42.860 --> 00:29:44.860
and that's simply seen from the mountain,

00:29:44.860 --> 00:29:45.860
the wind-away side.

00:29:45.860 --> 00:29:46.860
So,

00:29:46.860 --> 00:29:47.860
back side

00:29:47.860 --> 00:29:48.860
of the mountain,

00:29:48.860 --> 00:29:50.860
when the air mass

00:29:50.860 --> 00:29:51.860
hits that side.

00:29:51.860 --> 00:29:52.860
Or,

00:29:52.860 --> 00:29:53.860
in this sense,

00:29:53.860 --> 00:29:54.860
maybe a house,

00:29:54.860 --> 00:29:55.860
a lee side of the house,

00:29:55.860 --> 00:29:56.860
and a windward side of the house.

00:29:56.860 --> 00:29:57.860
On landing it's

00:29:57.860 --> 00:29:58.860
exactly the same.

00:29:58.860 --> 00:29:59.860
We can

00:29:59.860 --> 00:30:00.860
though, build up windward layers,

00:30:00.860 --> 00:30:01.860
build up,

00:30:01.860 --> 00:30:02.860
seen from the landing site,

00:30:02.860 --> 00:30:03.860
on the windward side,

00:30:03.860 --> 00:30:05.860
facing the wind.

00:30:05.860 --> 00:30:06.860
Right.

00:30:06.860 --> 00:30:07.860
About windward and lee,

00:30:07.860 --> 00:30:08.860
in particular keeps coming up

00:30:08.860 --> 00:30:10.860
during the course

00:30:10.860 --> 00:30:11.860
of your training

00:30:11.860 --> 00:30:14.630
and in the theory exam.

00:30:14.630 --> 00:30:15.630
Then we can

00:30:15.630 --> 00:30:17.630
to the last

00:30:17.630 --> 00:30:18.630
weather phenomenon,

00:30:18.630 --> 00:30:20.630
which is about wind,

00:30:20.630 --> 00:30:21.980
which is also very,

00:30:21.980 --> 00:30:22.980
very important for us,

00:30:22.980 --> 00:30:23.980
for paraglider pilots.

00:30:23.980 --> 00:30:24.980
And it's

00:30:24.980 --> 00:30:25.980
about

00:30:25.980 --> 00:30:26.980
us understanding

00:30:26.980 --> 00:30:27.980
the Venturi effect,

00:30:27.980 --> 00:30:29.980
the so-called Venturi effect,

00:30:29.980 --> 00:30:31.980
you might already

00:30:31.980 --> 00:30:32.980
from aerodynamic theory

00:30:32.980 --> 00:30:33.980
be familiar with this,

00:30:33.980 --> 00:30:35.980
the so-called concept.

00:30:35.980 --> 00:30:37.980
With the Venturi effect

00:30:37.980 --> 00:30:38.980
in there

00:30:38.980 --> 00:30:39.980
it's about,

00:30:39.980 --> 00:30:40.980
whenever

00:30:40.980 --> 00:30:42.980
a wind flow

00:30:42.980 --> 00:30:43.980
or air masses

00:30:43.980 --> 00:30:44.980
are forced

00:30:44.980 --> 00:30:46.020
to,

00:30:46.020 --> 00:30:47.020
narrow.

00:30:47.020 --> 00:30:48.020
So as a

00:30:48.020 --> 00:30:49.020
first example,

00:30:49.020 --> 00:30:50.020
for example a valley,

00:30:50.020 --> 00:30:51.020
if there's a broad valley,

00:30:51.020 --> 00:30:53.020
that suddenly narrows.

00:30:53.020 --> 00:30:54.020
And the wind,

00:30:54.020 --> 00:30:55.020
that flows through,

00:30:55.020 --> 00:30:56.020
becomes a valley wind,

00:30:56.020 --> 00:30:57.020
for example,

00:30:57.020 --> 00:30:58.020
the Gitz,

00:30:58.020 --> 00:30:59.020
in the narrowing

00:30:59.020 --> 00:31:00.020
of the valley,

00:31:00.020 --> 00:31:01.020
a wind acceleration.

00:31:01.020 --> 00:31:02.020
So we have

00:31:02.020 --> 00:31:03.020
significantly stronger wind,

00:31:03.020 --> 00:31:04.020
than

00:31:04.020 --> 00:31:05.020
in the wide part

00:31:05.020 --> 00:31:06.020
of the valley.

00:31:06.020 --> 00:31:07.020
Accordingly,

00:31:07.020 --> 00:31:08.020
when you of course

00:31:08.020 --> 00:31:09.020
fly,

00:31:09.020 --> 00:31:10.020
when you expect a lot of wind,

00:31:10.020 --> 00:31:11.020
that you in an

00:31:11.020 --> 00:31:12.020
open valley exit

00:31:12.020 --> 00:31:13.020
also in a narrow

00:31:13.020 --> 00:31:14.020
slot,

00:31:14.020 --> 00:31:15.020
for example.

00:31:15.020 --> 00:31:17.660
That's the Venturi effect.

00:31:17.660 --> 00:31:18.660
The same Venturi effect,

00:31:18.660 --> 00:31:19.660
you also get

00:31:19.660 --> 00:31:20.660
on a mountain

00:31:20.660 --> 00:31:21.660
or on a hill.

00:31:21.660 --> 00:31:23.660
When my air mass comes,

00:31:23.660 --> 00:31:24.660
you can imagine,

00:31:24.660 --> 00:31:25.660
in nice parallel lines,

00:31:25.660 --> 00:31:27.660
where the wind comes from.

00:31:27.660 --> 00:31:28.660
And then,

00:31:28.660 --> 00:31:29.660
we have a hill,

00:31:29.660 --> 00:31:30.660
where the air mass

00:31:30.660 --> 00:31:31.660
is forced to rise

00:31:31.660 --> 00:31:32.660
and accordingly

00:31:32.660 --> 00:31:34.660
to a narrowing

00:31:34.660 --> 00:31:36.660
on the hill

00:31:36.660 --> 00:31:37.660
or on the mountain

00:31:37.660 --> 00:31:38.660
is forced.

00:31:38.660 --> 00:31:39.660
And accordingly

00:31:39.660 --> 00:31:40.660
the wind speed

00:31:40.660 --> 00:31:41.660
on the mountain

00:31:41.660 --> 00:31:42.660
at the top is the strongest.

00:31:42.660 --> 00:31:43.660
So,

00:31:43.660 --> 00:31:44.660
when we once on the mountain

00:31:44.660 --> 00:31:45.660
stand

00:31:45.660 --> 00:31:46.660
and want to launch

00:31:46.660 --> 00:31:47.660
on the hill,

00:31:47.660 --> 00:31:48.660
and there's

00:31:48.660 --> 00:31:49.660
very strong wind,

00:31:49.660 --> 00:31:51.660
afterwards a descent,

00:31:51.660 --> 00:31:52.660
if of course

00:31:52.660 --> 00:31:54.660
with the paraglider

00:31:54.660 --> 00:31:55.660
a few hundred metres

00:31:55.660 --> 00:31:56.660
and then we notice,

00:31:56.660 --> 00:31:57.660
that in the lower layer

00:31:57.660 --> 00:31:58.660
most of the wind

00:31:58.660 --> 00:31:59.660
is much, much weaker,

00:31:59.660 --> 00:32:00.660
than really

00:32:00.660 --> 00:32:01.660
at the very top,

00:32:01.660 --> 00:32:03.660
full compression in there.

00:32:03.660 --> 00:32:04.660
Is of course something,

00:32:04.660 --> 00:32:05.660
that you

00:32:05.660 --> 00:32:06.660
maybe with soaring

00:32:06.660 --> 00:32:08.660
in flying practice

00:32:08.660 --> 00:32:10.660
or in real flight have already done.

00:32:10.660 --> 00:32:11.660
Of course important

00:32:11.660 --> 00:32:12.660
is,

00:32:12.660 --> 00:32:13.660
when we stay in exactly the area

00:32:13.660 --> 00:32:14.660
stay,

00:32:14.660 --> 00:32:15.660
where there's lift,

00:32:15.660 --> 00:32:17.660
where the wind is rising.

00:32:17.660 --> 00:32:18.660
But really important,

00:32:18.660 --> 00:32:19.660
at the top on the ridges

00:32:19.660 --> 00:32:20.660
for the most part

00:32:20.660 --> 00:32:21.660
an acceleration

00:32:21.660 --> 00:32:22.660
of the wind.

00:32:22.660 --> 00:32:23.660
Acting,

00:32:23.660 --> 00:32:24.660
when the Venturi effect

00:32:24.660 --> 00:32:28.130
right.

00:32:28.130 --> 00:32:29.130
Now we have wind,

00:32:29.130 --> 00:32:30.130
we have it,

00:32:30.130 --> 00:32:31.130
we have also learned,

00:32:31.130 --> 00:32:32.130
low-pressure area,

00:32:32.130 --> 00:32:33.130
high-pressure area,

00:32:33.130 --> 00:32:34.130
if you learn

00:32:34.130 --> 00:32:35.130
from the isobars

00:32:35.130 --> 00:32:36.130
to read wind,

00:32:36.130 --> 00:32:37.130
wind strength,

00:32:37.130 --> 00:32:39.130
maybe also read,

00:32:39.130 --> 00:32:40.130
because the closer,

00:32:40.130 --> 00:32:42.130
the isobars

00:32:42.130 --> 00:32:43.130
are together,

00:32:43.130 --> 00:32:45.220
the stronger the wind.

00:32:45.220 --> 00:32:46.220
And the wider

00:32:46.220 --> 00:32:47.220
and farther,

00:32:47.220 --> 00:32:48.220
the isobars are,

00:32:48.220 --> 00:32:49.220
think,

00:32:49.220 --> 00:32:50.220
of a topographic map,

00:32:50.220 --> 00:32:51.220
a landscape map,

00:32:51.220 --> 00:32:52.220
the wider apart,

00:32:52.220 --> 00:32:53.220
the isobars are,

00:32:53.220 --> 00:32:55.220
the weaker

00:32:55.220 --> 00:32:56.220
the pressure gradient,

00:32:56.220 --> 00:32:57.220
the,

00:32:57.220 --> 00:32:58.220
weaker,

00:32:58.220 --> 00:32:59.220
is also the equalisation flow

00:32:59.220 --> 00:33:00.220
between the pressure areas.

00:33:00.220 --> 00:33:01.320
It's really important,

00:33:01.320 --> 00:33:03.320
that we put it together,

00:33:03.320 --> 00:33:05.320
the different topic areas,

00:33:05.320 --> 00:33:06.320
that we're now looking at,

00:33:06.320 --> 00:33:07.320
and the more,

00:33:07.320 --> 00:33:08.320
the understanding becomes,

00:33:08.320 --> 00:33:10.320
of what's happening with the air masses,

00:33:10.320 --> 00:33:11.320
happens,

00:33:11.320 --> 00:33:12.320
the more you can also

00:33:12.320 --> 00:33:13.320
put together,

00:33:13.320 --> 00:33:14.320
and it's like a puzzle,

00:33:14.320 --> 00:33:16.320
the pieces fit together interestingly,

00:33:16.320 --> 00:33:19.320
and then flying weather

00:33:19.320 --> 00:33:21.320
really becomes an interesting field,

00:33:21.320 --> 00:33:22.320
and we really enjoy it,

00:33:22.320 --> 00:33:24.320
when you understand the connections too

00:33:24.320 --> 00:33:26.320
and really understand the basics.

00:33:26.320 --> 00:33:28.320
And that's why this course is so important,

00:33:28.320 --> 00:33:30.320
that you really understand the basics,

00:33:30.320 --> 00:33:32.320
and don't just learn it by rote.

00:33:32.320 --> 00:33:35.320
And we'll continue with this,

00:33:35.320 --> 00:33:36.320
in the next slide.

00:33:36.320 --> 00:33:38.220
The next topic,

00:33:38.220 --> 00:33:39.220
that we'll go into,

00:33:39.220 --> 00:33:40.220
is actually the only thing,

00:33:40.220 --> 00:33:42.220
that we haven't explained on this isobar chart.

00:33:42.220 --> 00:33:43.220
On the isobar chart.

00:33:43.220 --> 00:33:44.220
What we haven't covered yet,

00:33:44.220 --> 00:33:45.220
are the fronts.

00:33:45.220 --> 00:33:47.220
Those are the coloured lines,

00:33:47.220 --> 00:33:49.220
the blue, red, and violet lines

00:33:49.220 --> 00:33:51.220
with various symbols on them.

00:33:51.220 --> 00:33:54.410
And they lead to very specific

00:33:54.410 --> 00:33:56.410
meteorological conditions,

00:33:56.410 --> 00:33:58.410
which for us as paraglider pilots

00:33:58.410 --> 00:33:59.410
are very, very important,

00:33:59.410 --> 00:34:00.410
that we understand,

00:34:00.410 --> 00:34:01.410
and the dangers

00:34:01.410 --> 00:34:03.410
of the fronts we know,

00:34:03.410 --> 00:34:06.180
but to understand fronts,

00:34:06.180 --> 00:34:07.180
let's go back,

00:34:07.180 --> 00:34:09.180
to how a front even forms,

00:34:09.180 --> 00:34:10.180
like a stationary front.

00:34:10.180 --> 00:34:12.180
And we have to come back to it.

00:34:12.180 --> 00:34:14.210
The air mass,

00:34:14.210 --> 00:34:16.240
on the globe,

00:34:16.240 --> 00:34:17.240
heats up differently,

00:34:17.240 --> 00:34:19.240
with the colder air mass

00:34:19.240 --> 00:34:20.240
in the polar regions,

00:34:20.240 --> 00:34:22.240
and with the warmer, moister air mass

00:34:22.240 --> 00:34:24.240
in the tropical regions,

00:34:24.240 --> 00:34:26.240
or subtropical regions.

00:34:26.240 --> 00:34:28.240
And as I mentioned before,

00:34:28.240 --> 00:34:29.240
an air mass describes,

00:34:29.240 --> 00:34:30.240
a region,

00:34:30.240 --> 00:34:31.240
an air,

00:34:31.240 --> 00:34:32.240
a volume,

00:34:32.240 --> 00:34:33.240
that has the same properties.

00:34:33.240 --> 00:34:35.240
Here we have two different air masses.

00:34:35.240 --> 00:34:36.240
And in between

00:34:36.240 --> 00:34:39.240
there's an air mass boundary.

00:34:39.240 --> 00:34:41.850
And this air mass boundary

00:34:41.850 --> 00:34:43.850
is described,

00:34:43.850 --> 00:34:45.850
by a front.

00:34:45.850 --> 00:34:48.140
We have the blue triangles,

00:34:48.140 --> 00:34:50.140
that describes a cold front,

00:34:50.140 --> 00:34:53.140
and with the red dots,

00:34:53.140 --> 00:34:54.140
so the round ones,

00:34:54.140 --> 00:34:55.140
graphics,

00:34:55.140 --> 00:34:57.140
that describes a warm front.

00:34:57.140 --> 00:34:59.140
And then there's also a mixed-

00:34:59.140 --> 00:35:00.140
form, an occlusion,

00:35:00.140 --> 00:35:02.140
which we'll later

00:35:02.140 --> 00:35:03.140
come to,

00:35:03.140 --> 00:35:04.140
that's the third form of a front.

00:35:04.140 --> 00:35:06.300
Now we can imagine,

00:35:06.300 --> 00:35:08.300
we have the various air masses,

00:35:08.300 --> 00:35:10.300
and now we have for example

00:35:10.300 --> 00:35:11.300
a low-pressure area,

00:35:11.300 --> 00:35:13.300
where there are vortices.

00:35:13.300 --> 00:35:14.300
Think of it,

00:35:14.300 --> 00:35:16.300
maybe an extremely strong hurricane.

00:35:16.300 --> 00:35:17.300
There's a huge vortex,

00:35:17.300 --> 00:35:18.300
it's like a mixer,

00:35:18.300 --> 00:35:19.300
that starts mixing

00:35:19.300 --> 00:35:21.300
the air mass.

00:35:21.300 --> 00:35:23.300
And accordingly

00:35:23.300 --> 00:35:25.300
fronts begin to form.

00:35:25.300 --> 00:35:27.300
A cold air mass pulls,

00:35:27.300 --> 00:35:29.300
from north toward the south.

00:35:29.300 --> 00:35:31.300
And when an air mass pulls,

00:35:31.300 --> 00:35:32.300
from south toward the north.

00:35:32.300 --> 00:35:34.300
And accordingly a frontal system

00:35:34.300 --> 00:35:35.300
starts to move.

00:35:35.300 --> 00:35:37.300
An air mass gets moved,

00:35:37.300 --> 00:35:40.300
and accordingly is pushed out.

00:35:40.300 --> 00:35:42.300
And so

00:35:42.300 --> 00:35:45.300
step by step the fronts form.

00:35:45.300 --> 00:35:47.300
So you'll notice here,

00:35:47.300 --> 00:35:48.300
my arrows in the direction,

00:35:48.300 --> 00:35:49.300
for the low-pressure area,

00:35:49.300 --> 00:35:50.300
that rotates,

00:35:50.300 --> 00:35:52.300
that the whole thing pulls

00:35:52.300 --> 00:35:54.300
into rotation

00:35:54.300 --> 00:35:58.130
and accordingly forms the fronts.

00:35:58.130 --> 00:36:02.020
And here you can

00:36:02.020 --> 00:36:04.020
see quite nicely,

00:36:04.020 --> 00:36:07.020
that first a warm front gets produced,

00:36:07.020 --> 00:36:08.020
the red line,

00:36:08.020 --> 00:36:10.020
and at minimum a cold front,

00:36:10.020 --> 00:36:11.020
that follows behind.

00:36:11.020 --> 00:36:12.020
Now you see,

00:36:12.020 --> 00:36:14.020
as one will explain shortly,

00:36:14.020 --> 00:36:16.020
is faster on the move,

00:36:16.020 --> 00:36:18.020
than a warm front.

00:36:18.020 --> 00:36:19.020
So, a cold front

00:36:19.020 --> 00:36:20.020
is almost double,

00:36:20.020 --> 00:36:23.020
as fast in its movement as a warm front.

00:36:23.020 --> 00:36:24.020
And accordingly,

00:36:24.020 --> 00:36:25.020
comes the,

00:36:25.020 --> 00:36:27.020
that the cold front,

00:36:27.020 --> 00:36:28.020
the warm front,

00:36:28.020 --> 00:36:30.020
eventually catches up,

00:36:30.020 --> 00:36:32.020
and you see it in the centre,

00:36:32.020 --> 00:36:33.020
of the low-pressure,

00:36:33.020 --> 00:36:34.020
forms,

00:36:34.020 --> 00:36:37.020
what we call occlusion,

00:36:37.020 --> 00:36:40.020
a mixed form of the two fronts.

00:36:40.020 --> 00:36:42.020
We'll now go into detail,

00:36:42.020 --> 00:36:43.020
into this,

00:36:43.020 --> 00:36:45.020
what that means,

00:36:45.020 --> 00:36:48.200
or what that looks like.

00:36:48.200 --> 00:36:49.200
We can see here,

00:36:49.200 --> 00:36:51.200
how the air masses simply rotate,

00:36:51.200 --> 00:36:53.200
how the various front systems form,

00:36:53.200 --> 00:36:55.200
the two air masses.

00:36:55.200 --> 00:36:56.230
Now we see,

00:36:56.230 --> 00:36:58.230
maybe a strong cold front there.

00:36:58.230 --> 00:37:00.230
That's almost the most important front,

00:37:00.230 --> 00:37:02.230
or the most dangerous front for paraglider pilots.

00:37:02.230 --> 00:37:05.940
Here comes a cold front.

00:37:05.940 --> 00:37:06.940
You can imagine,

00:37:06.940 --> 00:37:08.940
it pulls from left to right in the graphic,

00:37:08.940 --> 00:37:10.940
the cold air mass

00:37:10.940 --> 00:37:12.940
pushes itself underneath.

00:37:12.940 --> 00:37:13.940
It's heavier.

00:37:13.940 --> 00:37:15.080
Accordingly it pushes itself

00:37:15.080 --> 00:37:16.080
underneath,

00:37:16.080 --> 00:37:18.940
in a wedge-like form.

00:37:18.940 --> 00:37:20.940
We can see the shape

00:37:20.940 --> 00:37:22.940
of the line in the weather chart,

00:37:22.940 --> 00:37:24.940
is such a wedge form,

00:37:24.940 --> 00:37:25.940
where it comes from.

00:37:25.940 --> 00:37:28.160
Accordingly cold air

00:37:28.160 --> 00:37:29.160
pushes underneath,

00:37:29.160 --> 00:37:30.160
the warm air,

00:37:30.160 --> 00:37:31.160
which is lighter,

00:37:31.160 --> 00:37:34.160
and accordingly it gets pushed up.

00:37:34.160 --> 00:37:36.960
Accordingly there's large-scale lift,

00:37:36.960 --> 00:37:38.960
large-scale lift,

00:37:38.960 --> 00:37:53.950
across this distance.

00:37:53.950 --> 00:37:56.990
and it can always bring thunderstorms with it.

00:37:56.990 --> 00:37:59.990
And now you see the thunderstorms,

00:37:59.990 --> 00:38:02.910
also of course very strong wind, very strong gusts.

00:38:02.910 --> 00:38:06.100
That's of course extremely dangerous for paragliding.

00:38:06.100 --> 00:38:11.000
What's of course the problem with cold fronts,

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:13.360
ahead of a cold front,

00:38:13.360 --> 00:38:14.840
we usually have nice weather.

00:38:14.840 --> 00:38:17.600
It's such a phase, it's nice weather.

00:38:17.600 --> 00:38:20.720
Makes you want to fly, maybe there's also a bit of wind.

00:38:20.720 --> 00:38:23.560
In Switzerland it's often accompanied by westerly winds,

00:38:24.560 --> 00:38:27.360
or also a bit of Foehn, we'll come to that later.

00:38:27.360 --> 00:38:30.560
But they're usually accompanied by a bit of wind,

00:38:30.560 --> 00:38:33.160
but often there are good flying conditions ahead of the front,

00:38:33.160 --> 00:38:35.160
because the air mass becomes unstable.

00:38:35.160 --> 00:38:38.190
It rises, and that's where you want to be.

00:38:38.190 --> 00:38:41.190
Now if you've seen on this weather chart, on this isobar chart,

00:38:41.190 --> 00:38:44.190
which hopefully before a flight you always briefly study,

00:38:44.190 --> 00:38:45.390
that a cold front is approaching,

00:38:45.390 --> 00:38:48.190
then be really cautious about flying right then.

00:38:48.190 --> 00:38:50.990
Because with it comes a lot of wind

00:38:50.990 --> 00:38:53.190
and with it a lot of rising air masses,

00:38:53.190 --> 00:38:55.790
where you really can't land quickly.

00:38:55.790 --> 00:38:59.790
And I think the cold front is really brutal,

00:38:59.790 --> 00:39:01.990
and for conservative pilots especially,

00:39:01.990 --> 00:39:04.990
if there's a cold front on the day, you can leave it alone.

00:39:04.990 --> 00:39:07.990
Cold fronts come at 40 to 60 km/h.

00:39:07.990 --> 00:39:10.790
It can be relatively fast, very important.

00:39:10.790 --> 00:39:13.790
The wind can of course get much stronger, the thunderstorm corners.

00:39:13.790 --> 00:39:18.060
And it takes about six to twelve hours to cross Switzerland.

00:39:18.060 --> 00:39:22.400
So it can happen relatively quickly, right.

00:39:24.420 --> 00:39:28.580
So be careful with cold fronts.

00:39:28.580 --> 00:39:31.580
Really important is, if before a flight

00:39:31.580 --> 00:39:34.580
you should always check the weather radar

00:39:34.580 --> 00:39:37.580
and especially keep your eyes on the sky.

00:39:37.580 --> 00:39:39.580
Because there you can see thunderstorms coming,

00:39:39.580 --> 00:39:40.580
looks roughly like this.

00:39:40.580 --> 00:39:43.580
We'll cover the thunderstorm topic in more detail in the course.

00:39:43.580 --> 00:39:48.130
But for all those on foot, when thunderstorms come in a line,

00:39:48.130 --> 00:39:50.130
when you see on the weather radar what it looks like now,

00:39:50.130 --> 00:39:52.130
then it's always extremely dangerous.

00:39:53.130 --> 00:39:56.130
Because it's a very active front, the thunderstorms are very strong.

00:39:56.130 --> 00:39:58.130
And I can imagine it a bit like a line.

00:39:58.130 --> 00:40:01.130
And if you've seen such a thunderstorm line on the weather radar,

00:40:01.130 --> 00:40:04.130
then I personally would land very quickly.

00:40:04.130 --> 00:40:07.130
Even when the thunderstorms are still 100 km away,

00:40:07.130 --> 00:40:11.130
because they can cause very strong winds.

00:40:11.130 --> 00:40:13.130
And then there can be cold air gust fronts from thunderstorms,

00:40:13.130 --> 00:40:16.130
which are very, very dangerous for paraglider pilots.

00:40:17.130 --> 00:40:20.130
We'll get into the thunderstorm area of the theory course

00:40:20.130 --> 00:40:22.130
in a bit more detail later.

00:40:22.130 --> 00:40:24.350
But here about the weather radar.

00:40:24.350 --> 00:40:27.700
Important about the weather radar, one more practical tip,

00:40:27.700 --> 00:40:29.700
don't just look at the radar,

00:40:29.700 --> 00:40:30.700
but at the natural sky,

00:40:30.700 --> 00:40:31.700
because the radar images,

00:40:31.700 --> 00:40:33.700
they're usually 40 minutes old,

00:40:33.700 --> 00:40:35.700
or half an hour even after the fact.

00:40:35.700 --> 00:40:36.700
There are also current ones,

00:40:36.700 --> 00:40:38.700
but observe the natural sky,

00:40:38.700 --> 00:40:40.700
and don't just look at your phone,

00:40:40.700 --> 00:40:42.700
if you fly enough.

00:40:42.700 --> 00:40:44.280
Right.

00:40:44.280 --> 00:40:48.280
Then a small addition about thunderstorms.

00:40:48.280 --> 00:40:50.280
The closer to the centre,

00:40:50.280 --> 00:40:52.280
of a low-pressure area for example,

00:40:52.280 --> 00:40:54.280
that you move into this front,

00:40:54.280 --> 00:40:57.280
the more active a cold front is.

00:40:57.280 --> 00:41:00.280
If you only graze the very outermost tip

00:41:00.280 --> 00:41:01.280
of this front,

00:41:01.280 --> 00:41:03.280
like in the case here in Greece,

00:41:03.280 --> 00:41:05.280
it can be, that the whole weather phenomenon

00:41:05.280 --> 00:41:07.280
is just a bit of rain

00:41:07.280 --> 00:41:09.280
and not so terrible,

00:41:09.280 --> 00:41:10.280
for flying maybe,

00:41:10.280 --> 00:41:11.280
but be careful,

00:41:11.280 --> 00:41:13.280
we have a lot to do with showers.

00:41:13.280 --> 00:41:15.280
But if you're really right in the middle

00:41:15.280 --> 00:41:17.280
of the cold front,

00:41:17.280 --> 00:41:20.280
afterwards it's really very active

00:41:20.280 --> 00:41:23.280
and afterwards it's definitely nothing for flying.

00:41:23.280 --> 00:41:25.280
But if you only get grazed,

00:41:25.280 --> 00:41:27.280
you can in some circumstances still fly,

00:41:27.280 --> 00:41:29.280
and it leads to a slight destabilisation

00:41:29.280 --> 00:41:31.280
of the air masses.

00:41:31.280 --> 00:41:33.280
But here, rather for advanced pilots,

00:41:33.280 --> 00:41:36.280
but good to know with this gradation,

00:41:36.280 --> 00:41:38.280
that a front in the centre is always stronger,

00:41:38.280 --> 00:41:41.280
than in the outermost area of this front.

00:41:43.180 --> 00:41:46.180
Then we can move on to the second frontal phenomenon

00:41:46.180 --> 00:41:48.180
and that's the warm front.

00:41:49.620 --> 00:41:51.620
The warm front is like this,

00:41:51.620 --> 00:41:53.620
that a warmer air mass

00:41:53.620 --> 00:41:55.620
always leads in front,

00:41:55.620 --> 00:41:57.620
rides up onto a colder air mass.

00:41:57.620 --> 00:41:59.620
With air masses it's always about,

00:41:59.620 --> 00:42:01.620
which one is colder or warmer.

00:42:01.620 --> 00:42:02.620
It doesn't have to mean,

00:42:02.620 --> 00:42:03.620
that one is warm,

00:42:03.620 --> 00:42:04.620
you can have an air mass,

00:42:04.620 --> 00:42:07.620
where it's minus 20 degrees and the other air mass

00:42:07.620 --> 00:42:08.620
is minus 10 degrees,

00:42:08.620 --> 00:42:09.620
is also cold,

00:42:09.620 --> 00:42:10.620
but it's colder,

00:42:10.620 --> 00:42:12.620
than the other air mass.

00:42:12.620 --> 00:42:13.620
Or warmer.

00:42:13.620 --> 00:42:15.620
So a warmer air mass comes.

00:42:15.620 --> 00:42:17.620
Accordingly the air mass

00:42:17.620 --> 00:42:18.620
is less dense,

00:42:18.620 --> 00:42:19.620
a bit lighter

00:42:19.620 --> 00:42:23.620
and it glides up onto the cold air mass.

00:42:23.620 --> 00:42:25.620
And accordingly a warm front comes

00:42:25.620 --> 00:42:27.620
in such a wedge shape.

00:42:27.620 --> 00:42:29.620
Here we can mark it,

00:42:29.620 --> 00:42:30.620
the diagonal lines,

00:42:30.620 --> 00:42:31.620
the air masses,

00:42:31.620 --> 00:42:32.620
that ride up,

00:42:33.850 --> 00:42:35.850
form a diagonal line.

00:42:35.850 --> 00:42:36.850
And it makes for us,

00:42:36.850 --> 00:42:37.850
as paraglider pilots,

00:42:37.850 --> 00:42:38.850
actually much less danger,

00:42:38.850 --> 00:42:40.850
than a cold front,

00:42:40.850 --> 00:42:41.850
in this drop shape.

00:42:41.850 --> 00:42:42.850
And we can imagine.

00:42:42.850 --> 00:42:44.850
If I'm down there on the mountain,

00:42:44.850 --> 00:42:45.850
and we fly,

00:42:45.850 --> 00:42:46.850
then I see very much,

00:42:46.850 --> 00:42:48.850
early before the warm front,

00:42:48.850 --> 00:42:49.850
over the ground sky,

00:42:49.850 --> 00:42:51.850
I see high cloud layers,

00:42:51.850 --> 00:42:52.850
coming.

00:42:52.850 --> 00:42:54.850
The sky gets more and more milky.

00:42:54.850 --> 00:42:56.850
It's not really nice,

00:42:56.850 --> 00:42:57.850
for flying.

00:42:57.850 --> 00:43:01.850
And the air mass comes in slowly.

00:43:01.850 --> 00:43:02.850
And the indication,

00:43:02.850 --> 00:43:05.850
if it won't fly well,

00:43:05.850 --> 00:43:06.850
it's not so good.

00:43:06.850 --> 00:43:07.850
We see then,

00:43:07.850 --> 00:43:08.850
the warm front,

00:43:08.850 --> 00:43:09.850
much less dangerous,

00:43:09.850 --> 00:43:10.850
than a cold front.

00:43:10.850 --> 00:43:11.850
But logically,

00:43:11.850 --> 00:43:13.850
I wouldn't fly into a warm front

00:43:13.850 --> 00:43:14.850
either,

00:43:14.850 --> 00:43:16.850
it's also always associated with wind.

00:43:16.850 --> 00:43:18.850
If you also see,

00:43:18.850 --> 00:43:19.850
a warm front,

00:43:19.850 --> 00:43:21.850
it comes much more slowly,

00:43:21.850 --> 00:43:23.850
so it comes at 15 to 25 km/h,

00:43:23.850 --> 00:43:27.100
it needs 12 to 24 hours,

00:43:27.100 --> 00:43:28.100
or even more,

00:43:28.100 --> 00:43:30.100
to cross Switzerland,

00:43:30.100 --> 00:43:33.100
so it's usually a slightly longer process.

00:43:33.100 --> 00:43:34.100
When that means two days

00:43:34.100 --> 00:43:35.100
of no flying weather,

00:43:35.100 --> 00:43:37.100
and that brings ahead of it

00:43:37.100 --> 00:43:38.100
as discussed,

00:43:38.100 --> 00:43:39.100
high shading,

00:43:39.100 --> 00:43:41.100
which weakens thermal activity,

00:43:41.100 --> 00:43:44.100
weakens

00:43:44.100 --> 00:43:46.100
and brings really good flying weather.

00:43:46.100 --> 00:43:49.390
Within a warm front

00:43:49.390 --> 00:43:51.390
the only problem is,

00:43:51.390 --> 00:43:52.390
that there is,

00:43:52.390 --> 00:43:54.390
also for mountaineers for example,

00:43:54.390 --> 00:43:55.390
is,

00:43:55.390 --> 00:43:56.390
that when I'm down there,

00:43:56.390 --> 00:43:57.390
I can't see,

00:43:57.390 --> 00:43:58.390
through the cloud cover,

00:43:58.390 --> 00:43:59.390
and see,

00:43:59.390 --> 00:44:00.390
what's there,

00:44:00.390 --> 00:44:01.390
because within a warm front

00:44:01.390 --> 00:44:02.390
it can in some

00:44:02.390 --> 00:44:04.390
and certain circumstances form thunderstorms.

00:44:04.390 --> 00:44:05.390
So especially,

00:44:05.390 --> 00:44:06.390
within the occlusion,

00:44:06.390 --> 00:44:07.390
where they come together,

00:44:07.390 --> 00:44:08.390
it can in some

00:44:08.390 --> 00:44:10.390
circumstances build into huge thunderstorm towers,

00:44:10.390 --> 00:44:12.390
which are of course very dangerous,

00:44:12.390 --> 00:44:14.390
and bring very strong weather with them,

00:44:14.390 --> 00:44:15.390
hail,

00:44:15.390 --> 00:44:17.390
and you can't see at all,

00:44:17.390 --> 00:44:20.390
because the cloud layers cover it.

00:44:20.390 --> 00:44:22.030
I find,

00:44:22.030 --> 00:44:24.030
above us the cloud names,

00:44:24.030 --> 00:44:25.030
that come with the warm front,

00:44:25.030 --> 00:44:26.030
come,

00:44:26.030 --> 00:44:27.030
we'll just learn,

00:44:27.030 --> 00:44:28.030
the cloud names,

00:44:28.030 --> 00:44:29.030
we'll look at one more.

00:44:29.030 --> 00:44:30.030
But,

00:44:30.030 --> 00:44:32.030
I think it's good to know,

00:44:32.030 --> 00:44:33.030
the warm front

00:44:33.030 --> 00:44:33.070
comes usually with stratus-like

00:44:33.070 --> 00:44:37.030
clouds, so with cirrostratus,

00:44:37.030 --> 00:44:38.030
altostratus,

00:44:38.030 --> 00:44:39.030
nimbostratus,

00:44:39.030 --> 00:44:41.030
it's always associated with stratus.

00:44:41.030 --> 00:44:42.030
Because stratus means,

00:44:42.030 --> 00:44:44.030
and why those are cloud names,

00:44:44.030 --> 00:44:45.030
and how they look,

00:44:45.030 --> 00:44:46.030
we'll go into

00:44:46.030 --> 00:44:47.030
in another chapter,

00:44:47.030 --> 00:44:49.030
when we look at cloud names.

00:44:50.030 --> 00:44:51.030
But just remember,

00:44:51.030 --> 00:44:52.030
also cirrostratus,

00:44:52.030 --> 00:44:53.030
altostratus,

00:44:53.030 --> 00:44:54.030
nimbostratus,

00:44:54.030 --> 00:44:56.030
is also tested in the theory exam

00:44:56.030 --> 00:44:57.030
very likely,

00:44:57.030 --> 00:44:58.030
when the clouds drive,

00:44:58.030 --> 00:45:00.030
then you can basically

00:45:00.030 --> 00:45:02.030
already keep the warm

00:45:02.030 --> 00:45:04.030
in the back of your mind.

00:45:04.030 --> 00:45:06.860
Right.

00:45:06.860 --> 00:45:08.860
Here an image,

00:45:08.860 --> 00:45:09.860
of how it comes,

00:45:09.860 --> 00:45:10.860
the clouds look like this.

00:45:10.860 --> 00:45:12.860
Those are stratus clouds.

00:45:12.860 --> 00:45:14.860
Those are always quite closed

00:45:14.860 --> 00:45:15.860
cloud cover,

00:45:15.860 --> 00:45:16.860
that always sinks lower,

00:45:16.860 --> 00:45:17.860
as time passes

00:45:17.860 --> 00:45:19.860
as the front approaches.

00:45:19.860 --> 00:45:22.860
And the cloud forms look roughly like this.

00:45:22.860 --> 00:45:28.790
Then we can

00:45:28.790 --> 00:45:31.790
move to the chapter on occlusion.

00:45:31.790 --> 00:45:32.790
Occlusion,

00:45:32.790 --> 00:45:35.790
you don't actually need a lot of knowledge

00:45:35.790 --> 00:45:37.790
the theory exam asks about it but

00:45:37.790 --> 00:45:38.790
nonetheless tests it.

00:45:38.790 --> 00:45:39.790
It's a mixed form,

00:45:39.790 --> 00:45:40.790
of the two fronts.

00:45:40.790 --> 00:45:42.790
And as said,

00:45:42.790 --> 00:45:44.790
for us now

00:45:44.790 --> 00:45:46.790
in practice especially relevant.

00:45:46.790 --> 00:45:48.790
Is that an occlusion,

00:45:48.790 --> 00:45:50.790
often the sky is covered

00:45:50.790 --> 00:45:52.790
and so-called,

00:45:52.790 --> 00:45:53.790
thunderstorms occur.

00:45:53.790 --> 00:45:54.790
Those are thunderstorm towers,

00:45:54.790 --> 00:45:55.790
that are inside,

00:45:55.790 --> 00:45:56.790
because the cold front

00:45:56.790 --> 00:45:57.790
and the warm front catch up,

00:45:57.790 --> 00:45:58.790
it's faster.

00:45:58.790 --> 00:46:00.790
Can there back thunderstorms occur,

00:46:00.790 --> 00:46:01.790
if we're up front,

00:46:01.790 --> 00:46:02.790
you see,

00:46:02.790 --> 00:46:03.790
the thunderstorm towers not at all.

00:46:03.790 --> 00:46:04.790
And it's really important for us,

00:46:04.790 --> 00:46:05.790
and we know,

00:46:05.790 --> 00:46:07.080
that this can happen.

00:46:07.080 --> 00:46:09.080
So very detailed question,

00:46:09.080 --> 00:46:10.080
that doesn't have extremely much

00:46:10.080 --> 00:46:12.080
to do with flying practice

00:46:12.080 --> 00:46:14.080
or for most paraglider pilots

00:46:14.080 --> 00:46:16.080
isn't of great relevance,

00:46:16.080 --> 00:46:20.080
there are two characters of occlusions

00:46:20.080 --> 00:46:22.080
and that gets tested in the exam.

00:46:22.080 --> 00:46:23.080
(unclear)

00:46:23.080 --> 00:46:24.080
There's a so-called occlusion

00:46:24.080 --> 00:46:26.080
with cold-front character

00:46:26.080 --> 00:46:29.080
and occlusion with warm-front character.

00:46:29.080 --> 00:46:32.080
Accordingly on such an occlusion image

00:46:32.080 --> 00:46:34.080
seen with the two drawn lines

00:46:34.080 --> 00:46:36.080
one of these air masses

00:46:36.080 --> 00:46:37.080
was simply,

00:46:37.080 --> 00:46:38.080
(unclear)

00:46:38.080 --> 00:46:39.080
(unclear)

00:46:39.080 --> 00:46:49.080
Accordingly

00:46:49.080 --> 00:46:50.160
lines with cold-front character

00:46:50.160 --> 00:46:53.270
(unclear)

00:46:53.270 --> 00:47:01.890
(unclear) — questions and

00:47:01.890 --> 00:47:08.100
and the elements that are different here, for normal pilots.

00:47:08.100 --> 00:47:10.120
Right.

00:47:10.120 --> 00:47:13.120
Let's wrap up the recording briefly.

00:47:13.120 --> 00:47:14.120
A few tips.

00:47:14.120 --> 00:47:16.120
Here are the two charts, the basics,

00:47:16.120 --> 00:47:18.120
that come up most often.

00:47:18.120 --> 00:47:20.120
Important on the left-hand chart,

00:47:20.120 --> 00:47:21.120
summarised.

00:47:21.120 --> 00:47:22.120
To recap.

00:47:22.120 --> 00:47:24.120
We have different pressure areas.

00:47:24.120 --> 00:47:26.120
Think, where's the low pressure?

00:47:26.120 --> 00:47:27.120
Where's the high pressure?

00:47:27.120 --> 00:47:28.120
How does it rotate?

00:47:28.120 --> 00:47:30.120
Accordingly the air masses.

00:47:30.120 --> 00:47:31.120
High pressure clockwise.

00:47:31.120 --> 00:47:33.120
Low pressure counter-clockwise.

00:47:33.120 --> 00:47:35.120
There we have the wind direction.

00:47:35.120 --> 00:47:36.120
Wind direction.

00:47:36.120 --> 00:47:38.120
Picture pulling out a compass.

00:47:38.120 --> 00:47:40.120
From which direction does the wind come.

00:47:40.120 --> 00:47:41.120
Accordingly give it.

00:47:41.120 --> 00:47:44.120
When the isobars are close together,

00:47:44.120 --> 00:47:46.120
we have very strong winds.

00:47:47.240 --> 00:47:49.240
When they're far apart,

00:47:49.240 --> 00:47:51.240
then we have relatively weak winds.

00:47:51.240 --> 00:47:52.240
What does far mean?

00:47:52.240 --> 00:47:55.240
And as a Swiss reference example,

00:47:55.240 --> 00:47:57.240
if the isobars,

00:47:57.240 --> 00:47:59.240
if we take the size of Switzerland,

00:47:59.240 --> 00:48:01.240
are close together,

00:48:01.240 --> 00:48:03.240
the Swiss hectopascal gradient is important.

00:48:03.240 --> 00:48:05.240
Then we have relatively strong wind.

00:48:05.240 --> 00:48:07.240
Once the isobars are far apart,

00:48:07.240 --> 00:48:09.240
say twice over Switzerland and so wide,

00:48:09.240 --> 00:48:11.240
as Switzerland, then it's really weak wind.

00:48:11.240 --> 00:48:13.240
Accordingly we have here in the Mediterranean area

00:48:13.240 --> 00:48:15.240
very weak wind.

00:48:15.240 --> 00:48:16.240
And then of course in the centre

00:48:16.240 --> 00:48:18.240
of the high pressure, relatively weak wind.

00:48:18.240 --> 00:48:22.500
So, reading off wind direction and wind strength.

00:48:22.500 --> 00:48:24.500
Then we get asked about the chart as well.

00:48:24.500 --> 00:48:27.230
Then we have here the two charts,

00:48:27.230 --> 00:48:31.230
where we additionally see the fronts.

00:48:31.230 --> 00:48:33.230
And for that, we need to know mainly,

00:48:33.230 --> 00:48:36.230
what kinds of cloud forms come with the fronts.

00:48:36.230 --> 00:48:40.230
We have for sure thunderstorms in the cold front.

00:48:40.230 --> 00:48:44.230
We have maybe a bit of cumulus cloud formation.

00:48:44.230 --> 00:48:46.230
And...

00:48:46.230 --> 00:48:48.230
Sorry, just a moment.

00:48:48.230 --> 00:48:49.230
We have here a cold front.

00:48:49.230 --> 00:48:51.230
The triangles are very important.

00:48:51.230 --> 00:48:54.230
The shapes of the graphics are important.

00:48:54.230 --> 00:48:56.230
So, when there are triangular cold fronts,

00:48:56.230 --> 00:48:58.230
thunderstorms are definitely a topic.

00:48:58.230 --> 00:49:00.230
We have here a warm front,

00:49:00.230 --> 00:49:02.230
symbolised by the run with the round symbols.

00:49:02.230 --> 00:49:04.230
Accordingly we have the,

00:49:04.230 --> 00:49:06.230
the cloud cover,

00:49:06.230 --> 00:49:12.270
as we discussed.

00:49:12.270 --> 00:49:14.230
The low pressure is in the low pressure,

00:49:14.230 --> 00:49:16.330
with the already drawn lines,

00:49:16.330 --> 00:49:18.330
no joke.

00:49:18.330 --> 00:49:21.330
There's for sure a storm, since it's raining.

00:49:21.330 --> 00:49:23.620
And for example a Dane,

00:49:23.620 --> 00:49:25.620
always a high-pressure approach,

00:49:25.620 --> 00:49:28.620
it's a multiple-choice learner,

00:49:28.620 --> 00:49:30.620
and also tap.

00:49:30.620 --> 00:49:33.620
And I always remind you of the basic rules,

00:49:33.620 --> 00:49:36.620
that we covered with the two charts.

00:49:36.620 --> 00:49:37.620
Right.

00:49:37.620 --> 00:49:39.620
Then you're well prepared.

00:49:39.620 --> 00:49:42.620
For exam questions about isobar charts and the run-up.

00:49:42.620 --> 00:49:47.380
Then we can move to a huge topic,

00:49:47.380 --> 00:49:49.380
which is important,

00:49:49.380 --> 00:49:51.380
in the theory exam moved on.

00:49:51.380 --> 00:49:53.380
If you really want to paraglide well,

00:49:53.380 --> 00:49:55.380
if you want to go cross-country,

00:49:55.380 --> 00:49:58.380
then it's the thermal.

